WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.435 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.435 --> 00:00:04.383 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.383 --> 00:00:07.792 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.792 --> 00:00:10.552 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.552 --> 00:00:11.510 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Hello?

00:00:11.510 --> 00:00:13.190 align:middle line:90%
Can people hear me?

00:00:13.190 --> 00:00:15.740 align:middle line:90%
Are we good in the back?

00:00:15.740 --> 00:00:16.610 align:middle line:90%
Are we good?

00:00:16.610 --> 00:00:17.430 align:middle line:90%
Can people hear me?

00:00:17.430 --> 00:00:18.860 align:middle line:90%
Good, good, good.

00:00:18.860 --> 00:00:22.970 align:middle line:84%
OK, so today, we are going
to move on from counting

00:00:22.970 --> 00:00:26.930 align:middle line:84%
and start the last
unit on probability.

00:00:26.930 --> 00:00:29.278 align:middle line:90%
Probability is very important.

00:00:29.278 --> 00:00:31.070 align:middle line:84%
It's one of the most
important disciplines,

00:00:31.070 --> 00:00:34.820 align:middle line:84%
not just in computer science,
but in all of the sciences.

00:00:34.820 --> 00:00:36.950 align:middle line:84%
Please don't tell your
other science instructors

00:00:36.950 --> 00:00:38.780 align:middle line:90%
that I said this.

00:00:38.780 --> 00:00:40.550 align:middle line:84%
You use it in--
like we've already

00:00:40.550 --> 00:00:44.960 align:middle line:84%
seen it in this class with
the Miller-Rabin algorithm.

00:00:44.960 --> 00:00:47.900 align:middle line:84%
You also see it in other
randomized algorithms

00:00:47.900 --> 00:00:53.420 align:middle line:84%
that you'll see later in 6 1210,
1220, 5220 if you take that.

00:00:53.420 --> 00:00:55.950 align:middle line:84%
We see it in game theory,
information theory,

00:00:55.950 --> 00:00:59.920 align:middle line:84%
signal processing, cryptography,
machine learning, medicine,

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:01.570 align:middle line:90%
stats, forensics.

00:01:01.570 --> 00:01:04.260 align:middle line:90%
The list goes on and on.

00:01:04.260 --> 00:01:07.110 align:middle line:84%
But unfortunately, it's also
one of the least understood

00:01:07.110 --> 00:01:08.760 align:middle line:90%
disciplines.

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:11.970 align:middle line:84%
So there's a pretty
famous quote attributed

00:01:11.970 --> 00:01:16.950 align:middle line:84%
to Mark Twain, Benjamin
Disraeli, several other people.

00:01:16.950 --> 00:01:19.090 align:middle line:90%
There are three kinds of lies.

00:01:19.090 --> 00:01:25.020 align:middle line:84%
There are lies, there are
damned lies, and statistics.

00:01:25.020 --> 00:01:28.920 align:middle line:84%
So you can kind of lie with
probability and statistics

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:34.290 align:middle line:84%
by saying things that are true
that are also very misleading.

00:01:34.290 --> 00:01:37.530 align:middle line:84%
Common sense is often very
demonstrably completely

00:01:37.530 --> 00:01:42.180 align:middle line:84%
unreliable, which
we'll see in a moment.

00:01:42.180 --> 00:01:43.590 align:middle line:84%
There are many
graduate students,

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:45.550 align:middle line:84%
like even in our
department-- again,

00:01:45.550 --> 00:01:47.880 align:middle line:90%
don't tell people I said this--

00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:50.362 align:middle line:84%
they can do all sorts
of exciting maths.

00:01:50.362 --> 00:01:52.320 align:middle line:84%
But you give them a basic
probability question,

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:55.110 align:middle line:84%
and they don't know
where to start.

00:01:55.110 --> 00:01:56.850 align:middle line:84%
There are many
garbage papers that

00:01:56.850 --> 00:01:59.720 align:middle line:84%
are based on faulty
understanding of probability.

00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:06.470 align:middle line:84%
Even some of our colleagues
have some, let's say, issues.

00:02:06.470 --> 00:02:09.860 align:middle line:84%
Today, we are going
to look at an example.

00:02:09.860 --> 00:02:13.130 align:middle line:84%
Who has heard of the
Monty Hall problem?

00:02:13.130 --> 00:02:14.565 align:middle line:90%
Oh, nice.

00:02:14.565 --> 00:02:15.565 align:middle line:90%
Decent number of people.

00:02:15.565 --> 00:02:18.164 align:middle line:90%


00:02:18.164 --> 00:02:21.230 align:middle line:84%
So, yeah, we'll basically try
and use the Monty Hall problem

00:02:21.230 --> 00:02:24.080 align:middle line:84%
to illustrate that
it's really best

00:02:24.080 --> 00:02:26.210 align:middle line:84%
to just throw away
your intuition

00:02:26.210 --> 00:02:30.879 align:middle line:84%
and just fall back on rigorous
step-by-step analyses.

00:02:30.879 --> 00:02:37.040 align:middle line:84%
So the Monty Hall problem, it
kind of became famous in 1990

00:02:37.040 --> 00:02:40.790 align:middle line:84%
when this magazine
columnist named

00:02:40.790 --> 00:02:47.300 align:middle line:84%
Marilyn vos Savant received a
letter from a Craig Whitaker,

00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:49.350 align:middle line:90%
which read as follows.

00:02:49.350 --> 00:02:51.860 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you're on a
game show, and you're

00:02:51.860 --> 00:02:53.910 align:middle line:90%
given the choice of three doors.

00:02:53.910 --> 00:02:58.300 align:middle line:84%
Behind one door is a car and
behind the others, goats.

00:02:58.300 --> 00:02:59.500 align:middle line:90%
You pick a door--

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:01.830 align:middle line:84%
say, number 1--
and the host, who

00:03:01.830 --> 00:03:04.980 align:middle line:84%
knows what's behind the doors,
opens a different door-- say,

00:03:04.980 --> 00:03:07.110 align:middle line:90%
number 3, which has a goat.

00:03:07.110 --> 00:03:10.740 align:middle line:84%
He says to you, Do you
want to pick door number 2?

00:03:10.740 --> 00:03:13.805 align:middle line:84%
Now, the question is, Is it
to your advantage to switch?

00:03:13.805 --> 00:03:16.686 align:middle line:90%


00:03:16.686 --> 00:03:21.270 align:middle line:84%
And who thinks yes, it is
advantageous to switch?

00:03:21.270 --> 00:03:21.888 align:middle line:90%
Who thinks no?

00:03:21.888 --> 00:03:23.430 align:middle line:84%
Who thinks you're
better off sticking

00:03:23.430 --> 00:03:25.800 align:middle line:90%
with your original choice?

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:28.620 align:middle line:90%
Who thinks it doesn't matter?

00:03:28.620 --> 00:03:32.610 align:middle line:84%
OK, so it looks like most
people think that it's

00:03:32.610 --> 00:03:34.290 align:middle line:90%
advantageous to switch.

00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:36.540 align:middle line:90%
We've had a few abstentions.

00:03:36.540 --> 00:03:40.410 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to count those
as it doesn't matter.

00:03:40.410 --> 00:03:44.910 align:middle line:84%
So Marilyn replied that it's
indeed advantageous to switch.

00:03:44.910 --> 00:03:47.200 align:middle line:84%
If the car is behind the
originally picked door,

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:48.490 align:middle line:90%
then you lose by switching.

00:03:48.490 --> 00:03:51.040 align:middle line:84%
But if it's not, which
is twice as likely,

00:03:51.040 --> 00:03:53.830 align:middle line:90%
then you win by switching.

00:03:53.830 --> 00:03:57.190 align:middle line:84%
And, of course, she soon
received a torrent of hate mail,

00:03:57.190 --> 00:03:59.680 align:middle line:84%
including from professional
mathematicians,

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:02.800 align:middle line:84%
adamantly asserting
that she was wrong.

00:04:02.800 --> 00:04:05.260 align:middle line:84%
So the hypo that was
described in this letter

00:04:05.260 --> 00:04:07.900 align:middle line:84%
became known as the
Monty Hall problem

00:04:07.900 --> 00:04:12.175 align:middle line:84%
after the host, Monty Hall,
of the game show which

00:04:12.175 --> 00:04:16.480 align:middle line:84%
had games like this
where contestants

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:19.329 align:middle line:90%
faced very similar situations.

00:04:19.329 --> 00:04:21.410 align:middle line:84%
So today, we're
going to analyze it.

00:04:21.410 --> 00:04:24.430 align:middle line:84%
But first, can I get a
handful of volunteers to come

00:04:24.430 --> 00:04:27.370 align:middle line:90%
play Let's Make a Deal?

00:04:27.370 --> 00:04:30.760 align:middle line:84%
OK, so empirically, at least,
it looks like it's better

00:04:30.760 --> 00:04:31.670 align:middle line:90%
to switch, right?

00:04:31.670 --> 00:04:35.320 align:middle line:84%
Most people switched, and
most people won the prize

00:04:35.320 --> 00:04:36.940 align:middle line:90%
when they did that.

00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:39.320 align:middle line:84%
So even though there's only
one door with the prize,

00:04:39.320 --> 00:04:41.650 align:middle line:84%
it seems to be pretty
promising, right?

00:04:41.650 --> 00:04:46.050 align:middle line:84%
So let's see if we can
analyze this mathematically.

00:04:46.050 --> 00:04:49.360 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to solve the
Monty Hall problem using

00:04:49.360 --> 00:04:53.700 align:middle line:84%
what we call the tree method,
which is a very simple

00:04:53.700 --> 00:04:58.028 align:middle line:84%
and elementary approach that
doesn't rely on intuition.

00:04:58.028 --> 00:04:59.945 align:middle line:84%
It's just going to rely
on mathematical rigor.

00:04:59.945 --> 00:05:02.640 align:middle line:90%


00:05:02.640 --> 00:05:09.263 align:middle line:84%
So the tree method
uses four-ish steps.

00:05:09.263 --> 00:05:10.930 align:middle line:84%
We used to call it
the four-step method.

00:05:10.930 --> 00:05:12.305 align:middle line:84%
But I couldn't
for the life of me

00:05:12.305 --> 00:05:14.280 align:middle line:84%
tell you what the
four steps are if they

00:05:14.280 --> 00:05:15.990 align:middle line:90%
weren't written in front of me.

00:05:15.990 --> 00:05:19.380 align:middle line:84%
So I prefer to call
it the tree method.

00:05:19.380 --> 00:05:21.070 align:middle line:90%
Oh, I can't even count.

00:05:21.070 --> 00:05:22.270 align:middle line:90%
It kind of has five steps.

00:05:22.270 --> 00:05:23.630 align:middle line:90%
We've got a step zero.

00:05:23.630 --> 00:05:26.400 align:middle line:90%


00:05:26.400 --> 00:05:29.490 align:middle line:84%
Before you even
start, you really

00:05:29.490 --> 00:05:31.900 align:middle line:84%
want to make sure that
you know what question

00:05:31.900 --> 00:05:32.900 align:middle line:90%
you're trying to answer.

00:05:32.900 --> 00:05:40.098 align:middle line:90%


00:05:40.098 --> 00:05:42.750 align:middle line:84%
So before we can even
think about solving

00:05:42.750 --> 00:05:47.670 align:middle line:84%
a mathematical problem, we need
to know what the problem is.

00:05:47.670 --> 00:05:50.720 align:middle line:84%
We need to understand
the setup, make

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:53.540 align:middle line:84%
sure we know what we're
trying to ask before we

00:05:53.540 --> 00:05:54.870 align:middle line:90%
can start analyzing it.

00:05:54.870 --> 00:05:58.760 align:middle line:84%
So the letter from
this Mr. Whitaker

00:05:58.760 --> 00:06:01.440 align:middle line:90%
was not entirely precise.

00:06:01.440 --> 00:06:05.910 align:middle line:84%
So we've got to figure out
what axioms we're working with.

00:06:05.910 --> 00:06:09.540 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to
assume the following.

00:06:09.540 --> 00:06:12.462 align:middle line:90%


00:06:12.462 --> 00:06:23.815 align:middle line:84%
A prize is equally
likely to be in any box.

00:06:23.815 --> 00:06:28.444 align:middle line:90%


00:06:28.444 --> 00:06:31.730 align:middle line:84%
So, in principle, it's
possible that Monty Hall

00:06:31.730 --> 00:06:35.180 align:middle line:84%
tries to be tricky and tries to
get into the contestants' minds,

00:06:35.180 --> 00:06:36.930 align:middle line:84%
figure out what box
they're going to pick,

00:06:36.930 --> 00:06:39.830 align:middle line:84%
and put the prize somewhere
else or, alternatively, put

00:06:39.830 --> 00:06:41.663 align:middle line:84%
the prize somewhere
where they will pick it,

00:06:41.663 --> 00:06:43.760 align:middle line:84%
because it's an
exciting game show.

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:46.730 align:middle line:84%
But we're going to
assume that Monty is just

00:06:46.730 --> 00:06:48.150 align:middle line:90%
picking the boxes randomly.

00:06:48.150 --> 00:06:51.920 align:middle line:84%
So the prize is going to go
into a randomly selected box,

00:06:51.920 --> 00:06:56.960 align:middle line:84%
completely uniform, and then the
other two will have the goats.

00:06:56.960 --> 00:07:02.640 align:middle line:84%
We're also going to assume that
Marilyn or your colleagues,

00:07:02.640 --> 00:07:14.060 align:middle line:84%
whoever is doing the picking,
is equally likely to pick

00:07:14.060 --> 00:07:20.123 align:middle line:90%
any box for the first pick.

00:07:20.123 --> 00:07:22.290 align:middle line:84%
She doesn't know anything
about what Monty is doing.

00:07:22.290 --> 00:07:24.650 align:middle line:84%
She's just going to toss some
random coins in her head,

00:07:24.650 --> 00:07:27.750 align:middle line:84%
and uniformly, at random, she'll
just pick one of the boxes.

00:07:27.750 --> 00:07:32.012 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't really matter
where the prize is.

00:07:32.012 --> 00:07:37.280 align:middle line:84%
Now, after Marilyn
picks her box,

00:07:37.280 --> 00:07:46.880 align:middle line:90%
Monty must reveal a non-prize.

00:07:46.880 --> 00:07:50.020 align:middle line:90%


00:07:50.020 --> 00:07:53.970 align:middle line:84%
And moreover, it cannot
be in Marilyn's box.

00:07:53.970 --> 00:08:05.032 align:middle line:90%


00:08:05.032 --> 00:08:08.090 align:middle line:84%
So all that Mr.
Whitaker said was

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:10.270 align:middle line:84%
Monty did reveal
a non-prize that

00:08:10.270 --> 00:08:13.390 align:middle line:90%
wasn't behind the chosen door.

00:08:13.390 --> 00:08:16.520 align:middle line:84%
It's not entirely clear
that this must happen.

00:08:16.520 --> 00:08:18.400 align:middle line:84%
And, in fact, I believe
on the game show,

00:08:18.400 --> 00:08:23.028 align:middle line:84%
there were instances
where he didn't.

00:08:23.028 --> 00:08:26.500 align:middle line:84%
So we're just going
to assume that Monty

00:08:26.500 --> 00:08:29.710 align:middle line:84%
is going to reveal a prize,
regardless of whether Marilyn

00:08:29.710 --> 00:08:32.115 align:middle line:84%
picked the correct
box to begin with.

00:08:32.115 --> 00:08:35.813 align:middle line:90%


00:08:35.813 --> 00:08:47.620 align:middle line:84%
And, lastly, if Monty has a
choice, he picks randomly.

00:08:47.620 --> 00:08:55.520 align:middle line:90%


00:08:55.520 --> 00:09:00.780 align:middle line:84%
So if Marilyn has picked
a non-prize to begin with,

00:09:00.780 --> 00:09:02.840 align:middle line:84%
there's only one
other non-prize.

00:09:02.840 --> 00:09:04.730 align:middle line:90%
So Monty has to reveal that one.

00:09:04.730 --> 00:09:09.660 align:middle line:84%
But if Marilyn has picked
the prize box to begin with,

00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:11.960 align:middle line:84%
then Monty could,
in principle, open

00:09:11.960 --> 00:09:13.250 align:middle line:90%
either of the other two boxes.

00:09:13.250 --> 00:09:16.250 align:middle line:84%
And that would still
follow this rule.

00:09:16.250 --> 00:09:18.120 align:middle line:84%
So when Monty has
a choice like this,

00:09:18.120 --> 00:09:19.850 align:middle line:84%
we're going to say
that he tosses a coin,

00:09:19.850 --> 00:09:22.060 align:middle line:84%
and he's going to open
one of them at random.

00:09:22.060 --> 00:09:26.352 align:middle line:90%


00:09:26.352 --> 00:09:30.990 align:middle line:84%
So note that these
are all axioms.

00:09:30.990 --> 00:09:33.360 align:middle line:84%
We are just taking
them on faith.

00:09:33.360 --> 00:09:35.760 align:middle line:90%
They may or may not have merit.

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:38.270 align:middle line:84%
But if you accept
them, then you also

00:09:38.270 --> 00:09:43.395 align:middle line:84%
have to accept whatever
conclusions we draw from them.

00:09:43.395 --> 00:09:44.770 align:middle line:84%
But I should point
out that there

00:09:44.770 --> 00:09:48.460 align:middle line:84%
are other perfectly reasonable
sets of axioms that would lead

00:09:48.460 --> 00:09:49.810 align:middle line:90%
us to different conclusions.

00:09:49.810 --> 00:09:52.690 align:middle line:90%
Like, maybe Monty is very rude.

00:09:52.690 --> 00:09:57.560 align:middle line:84%
And if Marilyn has
picked the prize,

00:09:57.560 --> 00:09:59.780 align:middle line:84%
then he offers her
the option to switch.

00:09:59.780 --> 00:10:02.630 align:middle line:84%
And if Marilyn has
not picked the prize,

00:10:02.630 --> 00:10:06.860 align:middle line:84%
then he forces her to go
with whatever she picked.

00:10:06.860 --> 00:10:10.960 align:middle line:84%
This is a totally
reasonable interpretation.

00:10:10.960 --> 00:10:14.290 align:middle line:84%
And that would lead us to
a different conclusion.

00:10:14.290 --> 00:10:15.980 align:middle line:84%
Or, conversely, maybe
it's benevolent.

00:10:15.980 --> 00:10:19.580 align:middle line:84%
Maybe if Marilyn didn't
pick the prize initially,

00:10:19.580 --> 00:10:22.850 align:middle line:84%
he'll always try and
encourage her to switch.

00:10:22.850 --> 00:10:25.100 align:middle line:84%
But if she picked the prize,
he'll just be like, nope,

00:10:25.100 --> 00:10:26.225 align:middle line:90%
you got to stick with that.

00:10:26.225 --> 00:10:31.410 align:middle line:90%


00:10:31.410 --> 00:10:34.360 align:middle line:84%
So now that we've
got these axioms,

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:37.420 align:middle line:84%
we can now pose the
mathematical question,

00:10:37.420 --> 00:10:52.860 align:middle line:84%
What is the probability that
Marilyn wins by switching?

00:10:52.860 --> 00:10:59.810 align:middle line:90%


00:10:59.810 --> 00:11:04.560 align:middle line:84%
So yes, this is why
I singled you out.

00:11:04.560 --> 00:11:06.890 align:middle line:84%
I don't know where
you have gone.

00:11:06.890 --> 00:11:10.190 align:middle line:84%
Your colleague who
did not switch,

00:11:10.190 --> 00:11:13.268 align:middle line:84%
we're trying to analyze
this probability, which

00:11:13.268 --> 00:11:14.310 align:middle line:90%
is why I singled you out.

00:11:14.310 --> 00:11:17.480 align:middle line:84%
So I apologize for that,
but it's for the maths.

00:11:17.480 --> 00:11:20.540 align:middle line:90%
Don't take it personally.

00:11:20.540 --> 00:11:27.380 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now we have a
well-defined question.

00:11:27.380 --> 00:11:29.980 align:middle line:84%
So now we can analyze it
using the four-step method.

00:11:29.980 --> 00:11:34.730 align:middle line:90%


00:11:34.730 --> 00:11:36.770 align:middle line:90%
The first of our four steps--

00:11:36.770 --> 00:11:40.770 align:middle line:84%
well, the tree method,
which has four steps--

00:11:40.770 --> 00:11:43.445 align:middle line:84%
we need to figure out what
we call the sample space.

00:11:43.445 --> 00:11:57.840 align:middle line:90%


00:11:57.840 --> 00:11:59.940 align:middle line:84%
So whenever we're thinking
about a probability

00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:03.570 align:middle line:84%
problem, underlying
it is always what

00:12:03.570 --> 00:12:06.610 align:middle line:90%
we call a probability space.

00:12:06.610 --> 00:12:09.095 align:middle line:84%
And a probability space
consists of two things.

00:12:09.095 --> 00:12:27.060 align:middle line:90%


00:12:27.060 --> 00:12:32.180 align:middle line:84%
These two elements are a set,
which we call the sample space.

00:12:32.180 --> 00:12:44.471 align:middle line:90%


00:12:44.471 --> 00:12:46.380 align:middle line:84%
And for the purposes
of this class,

00:12:46.380 --> 00:12:49.620 align:middle line:84%
we're only going to be looking
at discrete probability spaces.

00:12:49.620 --> 00:12:56.880 align:middle line:84%
So S is going to be a non-empty
and countable, or finite, set.

00:12:56.880 --> 00:13:00.696 align:middle line:84%
We're not going to look at sets
like R or something like that.

00:13:00.696 --> 00:13:04.770 align:middle line:84%
So this could be a
set of three boxes,

00:13:04.770 --> 00:13:06.710 align:middle line:84%
or it could be the
natural numbers, something

00:13:06.710 --> 00:13:11.180 align:middle line:84%
like that, something that's
discrete and countable.

00:13:11.180 --> 00:13:15.180 align:middle line:84%
And then we also
have a function,

00:13:15.180 --> 00:13:21.530 align:middle line:84%
which we're going to denote by
the letters Pr, which maps S

00:13:21.530 --> 00:13:23.960 align:middle line:90%
into the unit interval 0 to 1.

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:28.550 align:middle line:90%


00:13:28.550 --> 00:13:37.312 align:middle line:84%
So this is going to be
a total function with--

00:13:37.312 --> 00:13:43.500 align:middle line:90%


00:13:43.500 --> 00:13:44.920 align:middle line:90%
I probably shouldn't use S here.

00:13:44.920 --> 00:13:45.770 align:middle line:90%
Let's call it x.

00:13:45.770 --> 00:13:53.328 align:middle line:90%


00:13:53.328 --> 00:13:55.840 align:middle line:84%
And, slightly oddly, when we're
talking about probabilities,

00:13:55.840 --> 00:13:59.100 align:middle line:84%
we use square brackets
instead of parentheses

00:13:59.100 --> 00:14:02.040 align:middle line:90%
to enclose the argument.

00:14:02.040 --> 00:14:06.040 align:middle line:90%
But this is just a function.

00:14:06.040 --> 00:14:09.110 align:middle line:84%
You can think of it
as, like, Pr of x.

00:14:09.110 --> 00:14:11.625 align:middle line:90%


00:14:11.625 --> 00:14:13.440 align:middle line:84%
so We're going to
have the requirement

00:14:13.440 --> 00:14:18.390 align:middle line:84%
that if you sum up Pr of x over
all of the x in your sample

00:14:18.390 --> 00:14:21.652 align:middle line:90%
space, you should get 1.

00:14:21.652 --> 00:14:24.110 align:middle line:84%
That's what it means for this
to be a probability function.

00:14:24.110 --> 00:14:32.400 align:middle line:90%


00:14:32.400 --> 00:14:35.650 align:middle line:84%
Oh, actually, why don't
we leave both of these

00:14:35.650 --> 00:14:38.700 align:middle line:90%
up and move onto this board?

00:14:38.700 --> 00:14:45.850 align:middle line:90%


00:14:45.850 --> 00:14:49.770 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this is called
our probability function.

00:14:49.770 --> 00:14:55.990 align:middle line:90%


00:14:55.990 --> 00:14:59.972 align:middle line:90%
And elements of s are what--

00:14:59.972 --> 00:15:01.430 align:middle line:84%
we're going to call
those outcomes.

00:15:01.430 --> 00:15:10.780 align:middle line:90%


00:15:10.780 --> 00:15:16.370 align:middle line:84%
So, we've got a sample space
S, which is a set of outcomes.

00:15:16.370 --> 00:15:18.310 align:middle line:84%
And we've got a
probability function,

00:15:18.310 --> 00:15:23.290 align:middle line:84%
which maps each outcome to
a number between 0 and 1.

00:15:23.290 --> 00:15:25.870 align:middle line:84%
And it should be the case that
all of those probabilities

00:15:25.870 --> 00:15:27.850 align:middle line:90%
should sum to 1.

00:15:27.850 --> 00:15:30.760 align:middle line:84%
Does that make
sense to everybody?

00:15:30.760 --> 00:15:33.070 align:middle line:84%
People reasonably
Happy with this?

00:15:33.070 --> 00:15:35.715 align:middle line:90%
Questions, comments, concerns?

00:15:35.715 --> 00:15:38.275 align:middle line:90%


00:15:38.275 --> 00:15:38.775 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:38.775 --> 00:15:42.340 align:middle line:90%


00:15:42.340 --> 00:15:46.180 align:middle line:84%
So our first objective is
going to be to figure out what

00:15:46.180 --> 00:15:47.515 align:middle line:90%
our sample space should be.

00:15:47.515 --> 00:15:50.360 align:middle line:90%


00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:54.540 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to do that using
what we call a tree diagram.

00:15:54.540 --> 00:16:01.540 align:middle line:90%


00:16:01.540 --> 00:16:05.680 align:middle line:84%
So, for the moment, we're going
to disregard the probability

00:16:05.680 --> 00:16:08.760 align:middle line:90%
function and just focus on S.

00:16:08.760 --> 00:16:10.510 align:middle line:84%
And then once we've
figured out what S is,

00:16:10.510 --> 00:16:14.390 align:middle line:84%
we can figure out how to assign
probabilities to everything.

00:16:14.390 --> 00:16:18.160 align:middle line:84%
So the tree diagram,
as you might expect,

00:16:18.160 --> 00:16:21.700 align:middle line:84%
it's going to be a diagram
in the shape of a tree, where

00:16:21.700 --> 00:16:24.700 align:middle line:84%
each level of the
tree represents

00:16:24.700 --> 00:16:28.380 align:middle line:84%
some step in the random
process we're trying to model.

00:16:28.380 --> 00:16:31.036 align:middle line:90%


00:16:31.036 --> 00:16:34.430 align:middle line:84%
So in the case of the
Monty Hall problem,

00:16:34.430 --> 00:16:38.200 align:middle line:90%
what might be the first step?

00:16:38.200 --> 00:16:40.240 align:middle line:84%
What's the first
thing that happens

00:16:40.240 --> 00:16:45.850 align:middle line:84%
in the Monty Hall problem, the
first source of randomness?

00:16:45.850 --> 00:16:47.110 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:16:47.110 --> 00:16:49.915 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: You pick a first door.

00:16:49.915 --> 00:16:51.790 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: OK,
there's something random

00:16:51.790 --> 00:16:53.120 align:middle line:90%
that happens even before that.

00:16:53.120 --> 00:16:54.680 align:middle line:90%
The answer was, you pick a door.

00:16:54.680 --> 00:16:55.780 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:16:55.780 --> 00:16:57.843 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:16:57.843 --> 00:16:58.760 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah.

00:16:58.760 --> 00:17:03.700 align:middle line:84%
So the first random thing
that happens is I, or Monty,

00:17:03.700 --> 00:17:08.000 align:middle line:84%
picks which door
the prize is behind.

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:11.410 align:middle line:84%
So that's going to be the first
level of our tree diagram.

00:17:11.410 --> 00:17:14.540 align:middle line:84%
So let's start drawing
out our tree diagram.

00:17:14.540 --> 00:17:16.270 align:middle line:84%
We're going to
have our root here.

00:17:16.270 --> 00:17:21.989 align:middle line:84%
And let's label this
with Monty hides prize.

00:17:21.989 --> 00:17:29.297 align:middle line:90%


00:17:29.297 --> 00:17:33.260 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to
have three edges, which

00:17:33.260 --> 00:17:37.982 align:middle line:84%
go to the three possibilities
for what happens here.

00:17:37.982 --> 00:17:41.060 align:middle line:84%
So it could be in door
A, door B-- actually,

00:17:41.060 --> 00:17:43.640 align:middle line:84%
why don't I call these
purple, gold, and silver?

00:17:43.640 --> 00:17:44.485 align:middle line:90%
Where's the eraser?

00:17:44.485 --> 00:17:47.930 align:middle line:90%


00:17:47.930 --> 00:17:48.640 align:middle line:90%
Here we go.

00:17:48.640 --> 00:17:53.570 align:middle line:90%


00:17:53.570 --> 00:17:58.240 align:middle line:84%
So we've got our purple box, our
gold box, and our silver box.

00:17:58.240 --> 00:18:02.810 align:middle line:90%


00:18:02.810 --> 00:18:04.720 align:middle line:84%
What's the next random
thing that happens?

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:10.460 align:middle line:90%


00:18:10.460 --> 00:18:11.380 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:18:11.380 --> 00:18:12.630 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: You choose the door.

00:18:12.630 --> 00:18:13.130 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah.

00:18:13.130 --> 00:18:14.056 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Same as last time.

00:18:14.056 --> 00:18:14.973 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah.

00:18:14.973 --> 00:18:17.383 align:middle line:84%
So as your colleague
said last time,

00:18:17.383 --> 00:18:18.800 align:middle line:84%
the next random
thing that happens

00:18:18.800 --> 00:18:24.680 align:middle line:84%
is Marilyn, or the
contestant, picks a door.

00:18:24.680 --> 00:18:28.040 align:middle line:90%
So M-- oh, dear.

00:18:28.040 --> 00:18:31.132 align:middle line:84%
Monty and Marilyn both begin
with the same letter, OK.

00:18:31.132 --> 00:18:32.340 align:middle line:90%
Let's just call this Student.

00:18:32.340 --> 00:18:38.800 align:middle line:90%


00:18:38.800 --> 00:18:42.700 align:middle line:84%
So now each of these
is going to split

00:18:42.700 --> 00:18:46.214 align:middle line:90%
into three more possibilities.

00:18:46.214 --> 00:18:52.240 align:middle line:84%
So our contestant can pick
purple, gold, or silver

00:18:52.240 --> 00:18:54.620 align:middle line:90%
for each of these three things.

00:18:54.620 --> 00:18:57.320 align:middle line:84%
Regardless of where Monty
has hidden the prize,

00:18:57.320 --> 00:19:06.645 align:middle line:84%
the contestant can
pick any of the doors.

00:19:06.645 --> 00:19:22.760 align:middle line:90%


00:19:22.760 --> 00:19:26.300 align:middle line:84%
What's the next random
thing that could happen?

00:19:26.300 --> 00:19:26.800 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:19:26.800 --> 00:19:31.300 align:middle line:90%


00:19:31.300 --> 00:19:32.735 align:middle line:90%
Were you raising your hand?

00:19:32.735 --> 00:19:33.860 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Sorry about that.

00:19:33.860 --> 00:19:34.860 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Oh, no.

00:19:34.860 --> 00:19:37.640 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: If Monty has a
choice of which door to reveal

00:19:37.640 --> 00:19:41.150 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE].

00:19:41.150 --> 00:19:43.670 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah, so if
Monty has the choice of door

00:19:43.670 --> 00:19:46.490 align:middle line:84%
to reveal, then he picks
one of the two remaining

00:19:46.490 --> 00:19:47.925 align:middle line:90%
doors randomly.

00:19:47.925 --> 00:19:50.415 align:middle line:84%
So, so far, we've
got three branches

00:19:50.415 --> 00:19:51.415 align:middle line:90%
where that could happen.

00:19:51.415 --> 00:19:54.642 align:middle line:90%


00:19:54.642 --> 00:20:01.350 align:middle line:84%
We've got both Monty and Marilyn
pick door P. So in that case,

00:20:01.350 --> 00:20:11.990 align:middle line:84%
Monty can reveal either G or S.
So let's make a branch for that.

00:20:11.990 --> 00:20:18.240 align:middle line:84%
Similarly, if they both pick
P, we could have either P or S.

00:20:18.240 --> 00:20:21.440 align:middle line:84%
And if they both
pick S, then here,

00:20:21.440 --> 00:20:26.085 align:middle line:90%
we could have either P or G.

00:20:26.085 --> 00:20:28.000 align:middle line:90%


00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:33.010 align:middle line:84%
Now, for the remaining
ones, we could

00:20:33.010 --> 00:20:36.130 align:middle line:84%
say that there's a
random process there,

00:20:36.130 --> 00:20:39.500 align:middle line:84%
where Monty is randomly picking
from a single element set.

00:20:39.500 --> 00:20:41.420 align:middle line:84%
So it's always going
to be the same thing.

00:20:41.420 --> 00:20:44.050 align:middle line:84%
We could consider it a
random outcome, though.

00:20:44.050 --> 00:20:47.385 align:middle line:84%
So we can also draw
these arrows here.

00:20:47.385 --> 00:20:59.920 align:middle line:90%


00:20:59.920 --> 00:21:08.320 align:middle line:84%
Kind of running out of space
here, so let's put this up here,

00:21:08.320 --> 00:21:10.520 align:middle line:84%
and let's label
it on this board.

00:21:10.520 --> 00:21:19.690 align:middle line:90%
So Monty reveals a zonk.

00:21:19.690 --> 00:21:23.080 align:middle line:84%
So this is the technical
term for a non-prize.

00:21:23.080 --> 00:21:26.850 align:middle line:84%
I think the non-prizes on
Monty's show were called zonks.

00:21:26.850 --> 00:21:28.230 align:middle line:90%
They weren't always goats.

00:21:28.230 --> 00:21:31.950 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes it was some
other ridiculous prize,

00:21:31.950 --> 00:21:35.490 align:middle line:84%
like a garbage can or
a potato or something.

00:21:35.490 --> 00:21:37.190 align:middle line:84%
But, yeah, they were
just called zonks.

00:21:37.190 --> 00:21:44.886 align:middle line:90%


00:21:44.886 --> 00:21:47.118 align:middle line:90%
So now, are we done?

00:21:47.118 --> 00:21:49.535 align:middle line:84%
Is there any other randomness
that we haven't modeled yet?

00:21:49.535 --> 00:21:55.380 align:middle line:90%


00:21:55.380 --> 00:21:58.650 align:middle line:90%
Who thinks yes?

00:21:58.650 --> 00:21:59.530 align:middle line:90%
Oh, OK.

00:21:59.530 --> 00:22:01.730 align:middle line:90%
So what are we missing, then?

00:22:01.730 --> 00:22:03.730 align:middle line:84%
Everybody seems to think
we're missing somebody.

00:22:03.730 --> 00:22:05.190 align:middle line:90%
Or are we just asleep?

00:22:05.190 --> 00:22:09.780 align:middle line:84%
It is very early in the
morning, I understand.

00:22:09.780 --> 00:22:12.330 align:middle line:90%
Are we missing anything?

00:22:12.330 --> 00:22:15.630 align:middle line:84%
Who thinks we're not
missing anything?

00:22:15.630 --> 00:22:18.420 align:middle line:90%
Well, a few hands, OK.

00:22:18.420 --> 00:22:23.490 align:middle line:84%
Well, yeah, it turns out that
this is all of the randomness.

00:22:23.490 --> 00:22:27.870 align:middle line:84%
You could think about a
different problem, where

00:22:27.870 --> 00:22:30.370 align:middle line:90%
Marilyn has a random strategy.

00:22:30.370 --> 00:22:32.700 align:middle line:84%
But for now, we're
just-- our question

00:22:32.700 --> 00:22:35.080 align:middle line:84%
is, Marilyn is always
going to switch.

00:22:35.080 --> 00:22:37.145 align:middle line:84%
What's the probability
that she wins?

00:22:37.145 --> 00:22:41.010 align:middle line:84%
So this is all the
randomness that we've got.

00:22:41.010 --> 00:22:47.380 align:middle line:84%
So now that we have
our tree structure,

00:22:47.380 --> 00:22:50.050 align:middle line:90%
we can label our outcomes.

00:22:50.050 --> 00:22:52.560 align:middle line:84%
And that'll tell us
what the set S is.

00:22:52.560 --> 00:22:58.800 align:middle line:84%
So the set S is just going to be
the set of leaves of our tree.

00:22:58.800 --> 00:23:04.980 align:middle line:84%
Each path corresponds
to some way

00:23:04.980 --> 00:23:06.835 align:middle line:84%
that the random
process could turn out.

00:23:06.835 --> 00:23:08.293 align:middle line:84%
Those are going to
be our outcomes.

00:23:08.293 --> 00:23:10.970 align:middle line:90%


00:23:10.970 --> 00:23:14.620 align:middle line:84%
So formally, we could
label these as tuples.

00:23:14.620 --> 00:23:19.890 align:middle line:84%
So let's say that
this one is PPP.

00:23:19.890 --> 00:23:24.050 align:middle line:84%
So that represents Monty
hides the prize behind door P,

00:23:24.050 --> 00:23:26.360 align:middle line:84%
Marilyn picks door
P, and then Monty

00:23:26.360 --> 00:23:30.980 align:middle line:90%
reveals a zonk behind door G.

00:23:30.980 --> 00:23:35.180 align:middle line:90%
This one's going to be PPS.

00:23:35.180 --> 00:23:39.260 align:middle line:90%
This one's going to be PG.

00:23:39.260 --> 00:23:42.590 align:middle line:84%
And now, I haven't
actually labeled this edge.

00:23:42.590 --> 00:23:47.000 align:middle line:84%
But if Monty hides the
prize behind door P,

00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:51.713 align:middle line:84%
and then Marilyn
picks door G, where

00:23:51.713 --> 00:23:52.880 align:middle line:90%
is Monty revealing the zonk?

00:23:52.880 --> 00:23:57.530 align:middle line:90%


00:23:57.530 --> 00:24:00.290 align:middle line:90%
S, yeah.

00:24:00.290 --> 00:24:05.900 align:middle line:84%
So let's label that, and we
can continue all the way down.

00:24:05.900 --> 00:24:09.510 align:middle line:90%


00:24:09.510 --> 00:24:15.770 align:middle line:84%
So S-- oh, I've just realized
that I've overloaded it.

00:24:15.770 --> 00:24:18.700 align:middle line:84%
It's a script S in my notes,
and so it looks different.

00:24:18.700 --> 00:24:20.110 align:middle line:90%
I'm sorry.

00:24:20.110 --> 00:24:26.190 align:middle line:84%
[LAUGHS] OK, so our squiggly S
is going to be the set of all

00:24:26.190 --> 00:24:35.415 align:middle line:90%
tuples, so x, y, z, in PGS--

00:24:35.415 --> 00:24:38.520 align:middle line:90%


00:24:38.520 --> 00:24:41.890 align:middle line:90%
oops-- cubed.

00:24:41.890 --> 00:24:45.900 align:middle line:84%
So it's going to be
triples of P, G, and S,

00:24:45.900 --> 00:24:55.490 align:middle line:84%
such that z is not equal to
x, and z is not equal to y.

00:24:55.490 --> 00:25:01.947 align:middle line:90%


00:25:01.947 --> 00:25:04.200 align:middle line:84%
So that's how we're
mathematically going

00:25:04.200 --> 00:25:07.150 align:middle line:90%
to represent our sample space.

00:25:07.150 --> 00:25:11.190 align:middle line:84%
So x is the door that Monty
hides the prize behind.

00:25:11.190 --> 00:25:14.100 align:middle line:84%
y is the door that
Marilyn initially chooses.

00:25:14.100 --> 00:25:17.020 align:middle line:84%
And then z is going to be
the door that Monty reveals,

00:25:17.020 --> 00:25:17.990 align:middle line:90%
which has a goat.

00:25:17.990 --> 00:25:21.580 align:middle line:84%
And by our rule, that door
cannot be either of the first

00:25:21.580 --> 00:25:25.875 align:middle line:84%
two, but anything else
is a valid outcome.

00:25:25.875 --> 00:25:32.050 align:middle line:90%


00:25:32.050 --> 00:25:34.510 align:middle line:84%
OK, do we have any questions
about the sample space

00:25:34.510 --> 00:25:36.270 align:middle line:90%
and how we compute it?

00:25:36.270 --> 00:25:45.382 align:middle line:90%


00:25:45.382 --> 00:25:53.680 align:middle line:84%
So our next step, now that
we've got our sample space,

00:25:53.680 --> 00:25:55.680 align:middle line:84%
we want to figure out
our probability function.

00:25:55.680 --> 00:26:10.420 align:middle line:90%


00:26:10.420 --> 00:26:13.360 align:middle line:84%
So we'd like to figure out
what the probability of each

00:26:13.360 --> 00:26:16.600 align:middle line:90%
of these outcomes is.

00:26:16.600 --> 00:26:20.490 align:middle line:84%
So to do this, we're going
to assign a probability

00:26:20.490 --> 00:26:22.785 align:middle line:84%
to every edge that we've
got in our tree diagram.

00:26:22.785 --> 00:26:25.680 align:middle line:90%


00:26:25.680 --> 00:26:29.400 align:middle line:84%
And so that's just going to
be the probability that if we

00:26:29.400 --> 00:26:33.300 align:middle line:84%
get to the source of that edge,
what's the probability that we

00:26:33.300 --> 00:26:36.390 align:middle line:90%
proceed along that edge?

00:26:36.390 --> 00:26:42.900 align:middle line:84%
So at the very beginning,
if we're at the root,

00:26:42.900 --> 00:26:45.300 align:middle line:84%
what's the probability
that, given

00:26:45.300 --> 00:26:49.865 align:middle line:84%
that we're at the start, Monty
hides the prize behind door P?

00:26:49.865 --> 00:26:52.480 align:middle line:90%


00:26:52.480 --> 00:26:52.980 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:26:52.980 --> 00:26:53.760 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: A third.

00:26:53.760 --> 00:26:56.040 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN:
One-third, yeah.

00:26:56.040 --> 00:26:58.470 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to label
this with one-third.

00:26:58.470 --> 00:27:01.050 align:middle line:90%


00:27:01.050 --> 00:27:02.135 align:middle line:90%
What about G?

00:27:02.135 --> 00:27:03.510 align:middle line:84%
What's the
probability that Monty

00:27:03.510 --> 00:27:05.270 align:middle line:90%
hides the prize behind door G?

00:27:05.270 --> 00:27:10.530 align:middle line:90%


00:27:10.530 --> 00:27:11.520 align:middle line:90%
Anybody?

00:27:11.520 --> 00:27:17.010 align:middle line:90%


00:27:17.010 --> 00:27:19.220 align:middle line:84%
I mean, yeah, arithmetic
is pretty difficult.

00:27:19.220 --> 00:27:21.900 align:middle line:90%
But I'll just do it for you.

00:27:21.900 --> 00:27:25.028 align:middle line:90%
It's also one-third.

00:27:25.028 --> 00:27:27.830 align:middle line:84%
And the probability that
Monty hides it behind door

00:27:27.830 --> 00:27:30.290 align:middle line:90%
S, also a third.

00:27:30.290 --> 00:27:31.285 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, question?

00:27:31.285 --> 00:27:34.127 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So they
have to add up to 1--

00:27:34.127 --> 00:27:36.210 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah,
that's a great observation.

00:27:36.210 --> 00:27:40.100 align:middle line:84%
So all of these
three probabilities

00:27:40.100 --> 00:27:45.470 align:middle line:84%
should add up to 1, because
if we're at this vertex here,

00:27:45.470 --> 00:27:47.280 align:middle line:90%
we should proceed somewhere.

00:27:47.280 --> 00:27:50.633 align:middle line:90%


00:27:50.633 --> 00:27:54.380 align:middle line:84%
So it wouldn't make a whole lot
of sense to have probability

00:27:54.380 --> 00:27:57.620 align:middle line:84%
1/3, probability 2/3,
and probability 1,

00:27:57.620 --> 00:28:00.895 align:middle line:84%
because then you have to
proceed down this path,

00:28:00.895 --> 00:28:03.270 align:middle line:84%
but then you also have to
proceed down one of the others.

00:28:03.270 --> 00:28:06.170 align:middle line:90%
It's a bit sticky.

00:28:06.170 --> 00:28:09.660 align:middle line:84%
So given that you're
at this vertex,

00:28:09.660 --> 00:28:11.250 align:middle line:84%
you've got to reach
a leaf somehow.

00:28:11.250 --> 00:28:13.320 align:middle line:84%
You've got to get
to some outcome.

00:28:13.320 --> 00:28:15.790 align:middle line:90%
So you've got to proceed.

00:28:15.790 --> 00:28:21.710 align:middle line:84%
So all of these edges
should sum up to 1.

00:28:21.710 --> 00:28:24.020 align:middle line:90%
Great observation.

00:28:24.020 --> 00:28:25.970 align:middle line:84%
It's not quite true,
though, that that

00:28:25.970 --> 00:28:29.030 align:middle line:90%
holds for the entire column.

00:28:29.030 --> 00:28:32.510 align:middle line:84%
So what happens if we
look at the next column?

00:28:32.510 --> 00:28:36.290 align:middle line:84%
So given that Monty hides
the prize behind door P,

00:28:36.290 --> 00:28:39.010 align:middle line:84%
what's the probability that
Marilyn then picks door P?

00:28:39.010 --> 00:28:43.880 align:middle line:90%


00:28:43.880 --> 00:28:46.370 align:middle line:90%
Any ideas?

00:28:46.370 --> 00:28:47.137 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:28:47.137 --> 00:28:47.970 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: One-third.

00:28:47.970 --> 00:28:50.090 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN:
One-third, yeah.

00:28:50.090 --> 00:28:53.430 align:middle line:84%
So Marilyn picks this with
probability one-third.

00:28:53.430 --> 00:28:55.880 align:middle line:84%
Marilyn doesn't
know or care what's

00:28:55.880 --> 00:28:59.180 align:middle line:84%
going on with where
the prize actually is.

00:28:59.180 --> 00:29:02.150 align:middle line:84%
She's just picking each door
with probability one-third,

00:29:02.150 --> 00:29:04.140 align:middle line:90%
regardless.

00:29:04.140 --> 00:29:08.050 align:middle line:84%
So we've kind of got the
same thing going on here.

00:29:08.050 --> 00:29:11.830 align:middle line:84%
Each of these three edges
has probability one-third.

00:29:11.830 --> 00:29:16.120 align:middle line:84%
But now the same holds true
for this branch, right?

00:29:16.120 --> 00:29:18.760 align:middle line:84%
If Monty has hidden the door--
or hidden the prize behind door

00:29:18.760 --> 00:29:21.710 align:middle line:90%
G, now the same logic applies.

00:29:21.710 --> 00:29:25.450 align:middle line:84%
Marilyn is still picking each
door with probability one-third.

00:29:25.450 --> 00:29:29.650 align:middle line:84%
So we've also got one-third
here, one-third here, one-third

00:29:29.650 --> 00:29:30.690 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:29:30.690 --> 00:29:34.330 align:middle line:84%
So it's not quite that all
of the edges in a column

00:29:34.330 --> 00:29:36.730 align:middle line:84%
add up to 1, but all
of the edges coming out

00:29:36.730 --> 00:29:40.060 align:middle line:90%
of a single vertex add up to 1.

00:29:40.060 --> 00:29:41.700 align:middle line:84%
And same thing for
this bottom branch.

00:29:41.700 --> 00:29:49.282 align:middle line:90%


00:29:49.282 --> 00:29:50.745 align:middle line:90%
Now, what about the last column?

00:29:50.745 --> 00:29:53.440 align:middle line:90%


00:29:53.440 --> 00:29:55.480 align:middle line:84%
If Monty has hidden the
prize behind door P,

00:29:55.480 --> 00:29:58.630 align:middle line:84%
and Marilyn has
also picked door P,

00:29:58.630 --> 00:30:01.680 align:middle line:84%
what's the probability
that we get to outcome PPG?

00:30:01.680 --> 00:30:04.750 align:middle line:90%


00:30:04.750 --> 00:30:05.913 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:30:05.913 --> 00:30:07.030 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: One-half?

00:30:07.030 --> 00:30:08.697 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN:
One-half, that's right.

00:30:08.697 --> 00:30:11.924 align:middle line:90%


00:30:11.924 --> 00:30:15.450 align:middle line:84%
And it's also one-half--
whoops, that's not a 2.

00:30:15.450 --> 00:30:16.440 align:middle line:90%
That's a 3.

00:30:16.440 --> 00:30:18.372 align:middle line:90%
There we go, one-half.

00:30:18.372 --> 00:30:21.560 align:middle line:84%
So probability one-half
for each of them.

00:30:21.560 --> 00:30:24.507 align:middle line:84%
We've got probability one-half
that the zonk behind G

00:30:24.507 --> 00:30:26.840 align:middle line:84%
is revealed, probability
one-half that the zonk behind S

00:30:26.840 --> 00:30:29.210 align:middle line:90%
is revealed.

00:30:29.210 --> 00:30:33.890 align:middle line:84%
And as we were saying before, if
Monty hides the prize behind P,

00:30:33.890 --> 00:30:38.195 align:middle line:84%
and Marilyn picks G,
Monty now has no choice.

00:30:38.195 --> 00:30:43.865 align:middle line:84%
So we're just going to say
that this is probability 1.

00:30:43.865 --> 00:30:47.660 align:middle line:84%
And same with this one--
this one also has one PSG.

00:30:47.660 --> 00:30:50.690 align:middle line:90%


00:30:50.690 --> 00:30:52.590 align:middle line:84%
And similarly, for the
other three branches,

00:30:52.590 --> 00:31:00.990 align:middle line:84%
we've got 1, one-half, one-half,
1, 1, 1, one-half, and one-half.

00:31:00.990 --> 00:31:11.020 align:middle line:90%


00:31:11.020 --> 00:31:13.810 align:middle line:84%
So do these edge probabilities
make sense to everybody?

00:31:13.810 --> 00:31:25.206 align:middle line:90%


00:31:25.206 --> 00:31:29.640 align:middle line:84%
So now, remember what the
probability function was.

00:31:29.640 --> 00:31:37.240 align:middle line:84%
We have to assign a
probability to every outcome.

00:31:37.240 --> 00:31:40.925 align:middle line:84%
The outcomes are the leaves
of our tree, not the edges.

00:31:40.925 --> 00:31:43.510 align:middle line:90%


00:31:43.510 --> 00:31:49.890 align:middle line:84%
So what is the probability that
we end up with outcome PPG,

00:31:49.890 --> 00:31:50.600 align:middle line:90%
for instance?

00:31:50.600 --> 00:32:00.120 align:middle line:90%


00:32:00.120 --> 00:32:00.810 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:32:00.810 --> 00:32:02.240 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: It would be 1/18.

00:32:02.240 --> 00:32:03.480 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: 1/18.

00:32:03.480 --> 00:32:04.755 align:middle line:90%
And how are you getting that?

00:32:04.755 --> 00:32:07.130 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: It's one-third times
one-third times one-third.

00:32:07.130 --> 00:32:11.840 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah, one-third
times one-third times one-third.

00:32:11.840 --> 00:32:13.610 align:middle line:84%
We're going to
multiply together all

00:32:13.610 --> 00:32:17.905 align:middle line:84%
of the probabilities along the
path from the root to that leaf.

00:32:17.905 --> 00:32:21.011 align:middle line:90%


00:32:21.011 --> 00:32:23.180 align:middle line:84%
So Monty hides the
prize behind door P

00:32:23.180 --> 00:32:25.580 align:middle line:90%
with probability one-third.

00:32:25.580 --> 00:32:28.190 align:middle line:84%
And then, conditioned
on that happening,

00:32:28.190 --> 00:32:31.580 align:middle line:84%
Marilyn then picks door P
with probability one-third.

00:32:31.580 --> 00:32:33.740 align:middle line:84%
So then there's
probability one-ninth

00:32:33.740 --> 00:32:37.100 align:middle line:84%
that we make it to
this vertex here.

00:32:37.100 --> 00:32:43.676 align:middle line:84%
And now that one-ninth is split
again among these two outcomes.

00:32:43.676 --> 00:32:47.090 align:middle line:84%
Does that make
sense to everybody?

00:32:47.090 --> 00:32:51.440 align:middle line:84%
So if we do that for
every outcome, we've got--

00:32:51.440 --> 00:32:56.480 align:middle line:84%
oops, 1/18, not 1/8,
another 1/18 for PPS.

00:32:56.480 --> 00:32:57.483 align:middle line:90%
Then what about PGS?

00:32:57.483 --> 00:33:01.470 align:middle line:90%


00:33:01.470 --> 00:33:02.430 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:33:02.430 --> 00:33:03.840 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: It'd
just be one-ninth.

00:33:03.840 --> 00:33:05.632 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah,
it's just one-ninth.

00:33:05.632 --> 00:33:08.580 align:middle line:90%


00:33:08.580 --> 00:33:10.925 align:middle line:84%
So same deal for the
first two layers,

00:33:10.925 --> 00:33:12.300 align:middle line:84%
but then in the
last layer, we've

00:33:12.300 --> 00:33:13.540 align:middle line:90%
just got a probability of 1.

00:33:13.540 --> 00:33:16.180 align:middle line:84%
We don't have to split again,
so it remains at one-ninth.

00:33:16.180 --> 00:33:19.140 align:middle line:90%


00:33:19.140 --> 00:33:21.160 align:middle line:90%
And once again, we can continue.

00:33:21.160 --> 00:33:31.070 align:middle line:84%
We've got 1/9 here, 1/18,
1/18, 1/9, and we can continue.

00:33:31.070 --> 00:33:37.578 align:middle line:90%


00:33:37.578 --> 00:33:40.960 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to justify
this more formally later.

00:33:40.960 --> 00:33:43.500 align:middle line:84%
But for now, just
take it on faith

00:33:43.500 --> 00:33:46.590 align:middle line:84%
that in order to get the
probability of an outcome,

00:33:46.590 --> 00:33:49.530 align:middle line:84%
you multiply together the
probabilities along the path

00:33:49.530 --> 00:33:52.230 align:middle line:90%
to that outcome.

00:33:52.230 --> 00:33:54.870 align:middle line:84%
Hopefully, it at least
makes intuitive sense.

00:33:54.870 --> 00:33:57.710 align:middle line:84%
But we'll reason about
it more formally later.

00:33:57.710 --> 00:34:02.975 align:middle line:90%


00:34:02.975 --> 00:34:11.940 align:middle line:84%
So now, we have
our sample space,

00:34:11.940 --> 00:34:13.710 align:middle line:84%
we have our
probability function,

00:34:13.710 --> 00:34:15.952 align:middle line:84%
so we've got the entire
probability space that we're

00:34:15.952 --> 00:34:16.910 align:middle line:90%
trying to reason about.

00:34:16.910 --> 00:34:19.760 align:middle line:90%


00:34:19.760 --> 00:34:28.460 align:middle line:84%
The next thing that
we want, we want

00:34:28.460 --> 00:34:32.705 align:middle line:84%
to figure out what we
call events we care about.

00:34:32.705 --> 00:34:41.120 align:middle line:90%


00:34:41.120 --> 00:34:47.920 align:middle line:84%
So an event is simply a
subset of our sample space.

00:34:47.920 --> 00:34:58.944 align:middle line:90%


00:34:58.944 --> 00:35:00.333 align:middle line:90%
So it's a set of outcomes.

00:35:00.333 --> 00:35:03.570 align:middle line:90%


00:35:03.570 --> 00:35:13.475 align:middle line:84%
So up here, we could think about
the event that Marilyn wins.

00:35:13.475 --> 00:35:16.400 align:middle line:90%


00:35:16.400 --> 00:35:19.835 align:middle line:84%
So what is that
formally as a set?

00:35:19.835 --> 00:35:35.070 align:middle line:90%


00:35:35.070 --> 00:35:35.640 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:35:35.640 --> 00:35:38.850 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Subset of [INAUDIBLE].

00:35:38.850 --> 00:35:40.660 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah, exactly.

00:35:40.660 --> 00:35:44.520 align:middle line:84%
So the answer was, it's
the subset of events

00:35:44.520 --> 00:35:46.090 align:middle line:90%
where x and y are different.

00:35:46.090 --> 00:35:53.610 align:middle line:90%


00:35:53.610 --> 00:35:59.640 align:middle line:84%
So the notation that we usually
use for events is the following.

00:35:59.640 --> 00:36:02.313 align:middle line:84%
We put the description of
the event in square brackets.

00:36:02.313 --> 00:36:05.300 align:middle line:90%


00:36:05.300 --> 00:36:22.811 align:middle line:84%
So this is just going to be the
set P, G, S, P, S, G, G, P, S,

00:36:22.811 --> 00:36:40.640 align:middle line:84%
G, S, P, S, G, P, S,
P, G. So the 6 outcomes

00:36:40.640 --> 00:36:44.270 align:middle line:84%
where Marilyn and
Monty originally

00:36:44.270 --> 00:36:46.430 align:middle line:84%
picked different doors,
and then Monty is

00:36:46.430 --> 00:36:48.205 align:middle line:90%
forced to reveal the last one.

00:36:48.205 --> 00:36:53.024 align:middle line:90%


00:36:53.024 --> 00:37:04.440 align:middle line:84%
Similarly, we could also define
other events like Monty opens

00:37:04.440 --> 00:37:24.540 align:middle line:84%
door P. So this is going to be
the set G, G, P, S, S, P, G, S,

00:37:24.540 --> 00:37:36.870 align:middle line:84%
P, and S, G, P. So does this
make sense to everybody?

00:37:36.870 --> 00:37:39.510 align:middle line:90%
Any subset of events--

00:37:39.510 --> 00:37:42.900 align:middle line:84%
or, sorry, any subset of
outcomes is called an event.

00:37:42.900 --> 00:37:45.360 align:middle line:84%
We can take our
English description

00:37:45.360 --> 00:37:49.025 align:middle line:84%
and then look at which actual
outcomes this corresponds to.

00:37:49.025 --> 00:37:56.180 align:middle line:90%


00:37:56.180 --> 00:38:00.190 align:middle line:84%
So what we want to
do now is figure out

00:38:00.190 --> 00:38:05.980 align:middle line:84%
what event we care about,
or possibly what events.

00:38:05.980 --> 00:38:08.790 align:middle line:84%
So what are the events that we
care about for this problem?

00:38:08.790 --> 00:38:15.160 align:middle line:90%


00:38:15.160 --> 00:38:15.880 align:middle line:90%
Anybody?

00:38:15.880 --> 00:38:28.400 align:middle line:90%


00:38:28.400 --> 00:38:30.650 align:middle line:84%
What was the probability
that we're trying to compute?

00:38:30.650 --> 00:38:31.622 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:38:31.622 --> 00:38:33.760 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
when Monty loses--

00:38:33.760 --> 00:38:35.280 align:middle line:90%
or Marilyn loses.

00:38:35.280 --> 00:38:36.280 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Pardon?

00:38:36.280 --> 00:38:37.630 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: When Marilyn loses.

00:38:37.630 --> 00:38:38.547 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah.

00:38:38.547 --> 00:38:41.265 align:middle line:84%
So the events Marilyn
wins, and Marilyn loses.

00:38:41.265 --> 00:38:44.584 align:middle line:84%
These are the events
we care about.

00:38:44.584 --> 00:38:58.580 align:middle line:84%
So we could say Marilyn
loses is the complement

00:38:58.580 --> 00:39:01.465 align:middle line:84%
of Marilyn wins, which we
denote with an overbar.

00:39:01.465 --> 00:39:05.810 align:middle line:90%


00:39:05.810 --> 00:39:07.900 align:middle line:84%
So these are the two
events we care about.

00:39:07.900 --> 00:39:20.620 align:middle line:90%


00:39:20.620 --> 00:39:35.730 align:middle line:84%
So the final step is
to compute the answer.

00:39:35.730 --> 00:39:39.380 align:middle line:84%
We've identified the
event that we care about.

00:39:39.380 --> 00:39:41.285 align:middle line:84%
So now we want to figure
out the probability

00:39:41.285 --> 00:39:42.475 align:middle line:90%
that that event occurs.

00:39:42.475 --> 00:39:46.616 align:middle line:90%


00:39:46.616 --> 00:39:50.223 align:middle line:84%
So we can extend the
probability function two events.

00:39:50.223 --> 00:39:53.770 align:middle line:90%


00:39:53.770 --> 00:39:57.495 align:middle line:84%
So if E is an
event, we can think

00:39:57.495 --> 00:39:58.870 align:middle line:84%
about the probability
of an event

00:39:58.870 --> 00:40:02.380 align:middle line:84%
just as we think about the
probability of outcomes.

00:40:02.380 --> 00:40:05.890 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to
define this to be

00:40:05.890 --> 00:40:12.850 align:middle line:84%
the sum over all
outcomes omega in E

00:40:12.850 --> 00:40:14.535 align:middle line:90%
of the probability of omega.

00:40:14.535 --> 00:40:23.404 align:middle line:90%


00:40:23.404 --> 00:40:26.830 align:middle line:84%
So hopefully, intuitively,
that makes sense.

00:40:26.830 --> 00:40:32.650 align:middle line:84%
All of these outcomes, exactly
one outcome is going to happen.

00:40:32.650 --> 00:40:35.770 align:middle line:84%
So if we're trying to figure
out the probability that one

00:40:35.770 --> 00:40:38.380 align:middle line:84%
of a set of outcomes
happens, it's

00:40:38.380 --> 00:40:40.630 align:middle line:84%
just going to be the
sum of the probabilities

00:40:40.630 --> 00:40:42.420 align:middle line:90%
that each individual one occurs.

00:40:42.420 --> 00:40:45.040 align:middle line:90%


00:40:45.040 --> 00:40:47.760 align:middle line:84%
So we know the probabilities
of each of the outcomes.

00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:51.055 align:middle line:84%
That's what we
just computed here.

00:40:51.055 --> 00:40:53.720 align:middle line:90%


00:40:53.720 --> 00:40:55.640 align:middle line:84%
So now we can use
that to compute

00:40:55.640 --> 00:41:00.380 align:middle line:84%
the probability of the
events we just talked about.

00:41:00.380 --> 00:41:04.585 align:middle line:84%
So what is the probability
that Marilyn wins?

00:41:04.585 --> 00:41:20.540 align:middle line:90%


00:41:20.540 --> 00:41:24.830 align:middle line:84%
So we have our set
of outcomes here.

00:41:24.830 --> 00:41:26.290 align:middle line:84%
What's the probability
of each one?

00:41:26.290 --> 00:41:42.980 align:middle line:90%


00:41:42.980 --> 00:41:46.440 align:middle line:84%
Now, what's the
probability of outcome PGS?

00:41:46.440 --> 00:41:46.980 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:41:46.980 --> 00:41:47.580 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: One-ninth.

00:41:47.580 --> 00:41:48.955 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN:
One-ninth, yeah.

00:41:48.955 --> 00:41:50.796 align:middle line:84%
That one's written
up there explicitly.

00:41:50.796 --> 00:41:55.860 align:middle line:90%


00:41:55.860 --> 00:41:57.365 align:middle line:84%
What about the
probability of PSG?

00:41:57.365 --> 00:42:01.170 align:middle line:90%


00:42:01.170 --> 00:42:02.725 align:middle line:90%
Same, one-ninth.

00:42:02.725 --> 00:42:06.270 align:middle line:90%


00:42:06.270 --> 00:42:08.143 align:middle line:84%
What about the
probability of GPS?

00:42:08.143 --> 00:42:10.800 align:middle line:90%


00:42:10.800 --> 00:42:12.562 align:middle line:90%
Also a ninth.

00:42:12.562 --> 00:42:14.320 align:middle line:90%
All of these are symmetric.

00:42:14.320 --> 00:42:23.670 align:middle line:90%


00:42:23.670 --> 00:42:24.625 align:middle line:90%
What's that, 2/3?

00:42:24.625 --> 00:42:27.830 align:middle line:90%


00:42:27.830 --> 00:42:31.590 align:middle line:84%
So we've got six events-- or
six outcomes, each of which

00:42:31.590 --> 00:42:34.230 align:middle line:84%
occurs with
probability one-ninth.

00:42:34.230 --> 00:42:38.040 align:middle line:84%
So if you add those all
together, you get 2/3.

00:42:38.040 --> 00:42:42.660 align:middle line:84%
So this seems to support
what we found empirically.

00:42:42.660 --> 00:42:46.490 align:middle line:84%
Marilyn wins with better
than probability one-half.

00:42:46.490 --> 00:42:48.227 align:middle line:84%
The probability that
she loses is going

00:42:48.227 --> 00:42:49.435 align:middle line:90%
to be the complement of this.

00:42:49.435 --> 00:43:01.298 align:middle line:90%


00:43:01.298 --> 00:43:04.340 align:middle line:84%
So it's going to be the sum
of the probabilities of all

00:43:04.340 --> 00:43:06.070 align:middle line:90%
of the other outcomes.

00:43:06.070 --> 00:43:09.060 align:middle line:84%
And we said that all
probabilities fit out to 1,

00:43:09.060 --> 00:43:12.050 align:middle line:84%
so this is going to be the
complement with respect to 1.

00:43:12.050 --> 00:43:15.020 align:middle line:90%


00:43:15.020 --> 00:43:18.095 align:middle line:84%
So as it turns out,
Marilyn was correct.

00:43:18.095 --> 00:43:20.150 align:middle line:84%
We didn't have to rely
on intuition or anything

00:43:20.150 --> 00:43:23.520 align:middle line:84%
like that, no ingenious
analogies, et cetera.

00:43:23.520 --> 00:43:27.060 align:middle line:90%
It's just arithmetic over Q.

00:43:27.060 --> 00:43:29.930 align:middle line:84%
And I think the hardest
part of this for many people

00:43:29.930 --> 00:43:35.450 align:middle line:84%
is resisting the temptation to
jump to some obvious conclusion.

00:43:35.450 --> 00:43:39.620 align:middle line:84%
It might be tempting to get
to the end of the tree diagram

00:43:39.620 --> 00:43:42.210 align:middle line:84%
and be like, oh, we've got six
outcomes where Marilyn wins,

00:43:42.210 --> 00:43:47.550 align:middle line:84%
six where she loses, So
probability 6/12 is 1/2.

00:43:47.550 --> 00:43:50.970 align:middle line:84%
So if we actually set
all of that intuition

00:43:50.970 --> 00:43:53.380 align:middle line:84%
aside, go through
everything formally,

00:43:53.380 --> 00:43:58.050 align:middle line:84%
it's all quite simple
and straightforward.

00:43:58.050 --> 00:43:59.620 align:middle line:84%
Does that make
sense to everybody?

00:43:59.620 --> 00:44:06.610 align:middle line:90%


00:44:06.610 --> 00:44:09.540 align:middle line:84%
So let's move on to
a different example.

00:44:09.540 --> 00:44:15.300 align:middle line:84%
Suppose I have
three strange dice.

00:44:15.300 --> 00:44:17.213 align:middle line:90%
So excuse my drawing--

00:44:17.213 --> 00:44:19.830 align:middle line:90%


00:44:19.830 --> 00:44:22.410 align:middle line:90%
whoops-- there.

00:44:22.410 --> 00:44:26.820 align:middle line:84%
OK, so I've got one
die that has 2 written

00:44:26.820 --> 00:44:32.340 align:middle line:84%
on two of the faces, so top and
bottom, 6 written on these two

00:44:32.340 --> 00:44:37.680 align:middle line:84%
faces, and 7 written
on those two faces.

00:44:37.680 --> 00:44:42.770 align:middle line:84%
Hopefully, that looks
vaguely cubical.

00:44:42.770 --> 00:44:44.715 align:middle line:84%
I've got a second
die, which is similar.

00:44:44.715 --> 00:44:47.380 align:middle line:90%


00:44:47.380 --> 00:44:52.540 align:middle line:84%
But instead of 2, 6, and
7, I've got 1, 5, and 9.

00:44:52.540 --> 00:45:00.870 align:middle line:84%
Then I've got a third one,
which has 3, 4, and 8.

00:45:00.870 --> 00:45:04.360 align:middle line:90%


00:45:04.360 --> 00:45:09.580 align:middle line:90%
So consider the following game.

00:45:09.580 --> 00:45:12.310 align:middle line:90%
I pick a die.

00:45:12.310 --> 00:45:16.720 align:middle line:84%
Now you pick one
of the other dies--

00:45:16.720 --> 00:45:19.420 align:middle line:84%
or dice-- after
seeing what I pick.

00:45:19.420 --> 00:45:23.090 align:middle line:90%
And we each roll our dice.

00:45:23.090 --> 00:45:25.035 align:middle line:84%
And whoever gets the
higher number wins.

00:45:25.035 --> 00:45:27.700 align:middle line:90%


00:45:27.700 --> 00:45:28.832 align:middle line:90%
Who should win?

00:45:28.832 --> 00:45:30.165 align:middle line:90%
Should I win, or should you win?

00:45:30.165 --> 00:45:32.830 align:middle line:90%


00:45:32.830 --> 00:45:33.660 align:middle line:90%
Who thinks I win?

00:45:33.660 --> 00:45:37.330 align:middle line:90%


00:45:37.330 --> 00:45:39.110 align:middle line:90%
OK, who thinks you win?

00:45:39.110 --> 00:45:43.770 align:middle line:90%


00:45:43.770 --> 00:45:47.850 align:middle line:84%
Who thinks we should just do the
tree diagram and figure it out?

00:45:47.850 --> 00:45:49.180 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, good call.

00:45:49.180 --> 00:45:50.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:50.190 --> 00:45:58.862 align:middle line:84%
So let's call these dice
R, G, and B. Yeah, let's

00:45:58.862 --> 00:45:59.945 align:middle line:90%
draw out our tree diagram.

00:45:59.945 --> 00:46:03.920 align:middle line:90%


00:46:03.920 --> 00:46:09.330 align:middle line:84%
So what happens if, say, I
pick the red die, and you

00:46:09.330 --> 00:46:12.630 align:middle line:90%
pick the green die?

00:46:12.630 --> 00:46:13.420 align:middle line:90%
Who should win?

00:46:13.420 --> 00:46:15.360 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

00:46:15.360 --> 00:46:20.650 align:middle line:84%
So we've got--
when I roll my die,

00:46:20.650 --> 00:46:22.270 align:middle line:90%
there are three possibilities.

00:46:22.270 --> 00:46:28.920 align:middle line:84%
I could either get
a 2, a 6, or a 7.

00:46:28.920 --> 00:46:32.700 align:middle line:84%
And now you roll the green
die, and you could have either

00:46:32.700 --> 00:46:36.790 align:middle line:90%
a 1, a 5, or a 9--

00:46:36.790 --> 00:46:38.510 align:middle line:90%
not minus 5, 5--

00:46:38.510 --> 00:46:46.174 align:middle line:90%
1, 5, 9, 1, 5, 9.

00:46:46.174 --> 00:46:50.704 align:middle line:90%


00:46:50.704 --> 00:46:53.230 align:middle line:84%
And now what is
the probability--

00:46:53.230 --> 00:46:57.490 align:middle line:84%
or, sorry, what
are the outcomes?

00:46:57.490 --> 00:47:00.942 align:middle line:90%
We have 9 leaves, so 9 outcomes.

00:47:00.942 --> 00:47:02.400 align:middle line:84%
How are we going
to represent them?

00:47:02.400 --> 00:47:15.670 align:middle line:90%


00:47:15.670 --> 00:47:18.610 align:middle line:84%
Well, we can do it basically the
same as how we represented them

00:47:18.610 --> 00:47:20.120 align:middle line:90%
up here.

00:47:20.120 --> 00:47:26.060 align:middle line:84%
We can just look at a
tuple of edge labels.

00:47:26.060 --> 00:47:29.440 align:middle line:84%
So our sample space
is going to be

00:47:29.440 --> 00:47:39.755 align:middle line:84%
the set 2, 6, 7, a Cartesian
product with 1, 5, 9.

00:47:39.755 --> 00:47:42.551 align:middle line:90%


00:47:42.551 --> 00:47:44.402 align:middle line:84%
So this is going
to be ordered pairs

00:47:44.402 --> 00:47:46.610 align:middle line:84%
where the first element is
one of these three things,

00:47:46.610 --> 00:47:49.410 align:middle line:84%
and the second is one
of these three things.

00:47:49.410 --> 00:47:53.040 align:middle line:84%
So this one, for
instance, is 2, comma 1.

00:47:53.040 --> 00:47:55.350 align:middle line:84%
This one is 2,
comma, 5, et cetera.

00:47:55.350 --> 00:48:00.650 align:middle line:90%


00:48:00.650 --> 00:48:02.575 align:middle line:84%
Now what are the
probabilities on each edge?

00:48:02.575 --> 00:48:07.520 align:middle line:90%


00:48:07.520 --> 00:48:08.900 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:48:08.900 --> 00:48:11.720 align:middle line:90%
One-ninth.

00:48:11.720 --> 00:48:14.937 align:middle line:84%
So those are the
probabilities on the outcomes.

00:48:14.937 --> 00:48:16.895 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, one-third on each edge.

00:48:16.895 --> 00:48:23.636 align:middle line:90%


00:48:23.636 --> 00:48:26.420 align:middle line:84%
So when I roll my die, I've
got a one-third chance each

00:48:26.420 --> 00:48:28.040 align:middle line:90%
of getting 2, 6, or 7.

00:48:28.040 --> 00:48:30.350 align:middle line:84%
When you roll yours, you've
got a one-third chance each

00:48:30.350 --> 00:48:32.400 align:middle line:90%
of getting 1, 5, or 9.

00:48:32.400 --> 00:48:36.220 align:middle line:90%


00:48:36.220 --> 00:48:39.010 align:middle line:84%
And it's going to be the same
for the other two branches.

00:48:39.010 --> 00:48:41.710 align:middle line:84%
So when we multiply
together the probabilities

00:48:41.710 --> 00:48:47.730 align:middle line:84%
along paths to leaves, we get
one-ninth for every outcome.

00:48:47.730 --> 00:48:52.354 align:middle line:90%


00:48:52.354 --> 00:48:54.400 align:middle line:84%
So when you have a
probability space

00:48:54.400 --> 00:48:57.580 align:middle line:84%
like this that's
particularly nice,

00:48:57.580 --> 00:48:59.940 align:middle line:84%
this is what we call a
uniform probability space.

00:48:59.940 --> 00:49:04.460 align:middle line:90%


00:49:04.460 --> 00:49:08.740 align:middle line:90%
So let's say S, comma, Pr--

00:49:08.740 --> 00:49:11.770 align:middle line:84%
so this is our
probability space--

00:49:11.770 --> 00:49:19.905 align:middle line:90%
is uniform if Pr is constant.

00:49:19.905 --> 00:49:26.270 align:middle line:90%


00:49:26.270 --> 00:49:28.060 align:middle line:84%
So in this case, it's
a constant function

00:49:28.060 --> 00:49:31.190 align:middle line:84%
that maps every outcome to
a probability of one-ninth.

00:49:31.190 --> 00:49:32.975 align:middle line:84%
So it's a uniform
probability space.

00:49:32.975 --> 00:49:35.810 align:middle line:90%


00:49:35.810 --> 00:49:38.812 align:middle line:84%
And uniform spaces
are particularly

00:49:38.812 --> 00:49:41.270 align:middle line:84%
nice because we don't even have
to worry about the addition

00:49:41.270 --> 00:49:42.950 align:middle line:90%
that we were doing before.

00:49:42.950 --> 00:49:46.250 align:middle line:84%
In order to figure out
probabilities of events,

00:49:46.250 --> 00:49:48.830 align:middle line:84%
you just count up how many
outcomes are in the event

00:49:48.830 --> 00:49:52.740 align:middle line:84%
and then divide by the
total number of outcomes.

00:49:52.740 --> 00:49:54.880 align:middle line:84%
So it just becomes
a counting problem.

00:49:54.880 --> 00:50:00.270 align:middle line:90%


00:50:00.270 --> 00:50:03.925 align:middle line:84%
So using that, what's the
probability that red wins?

00:50:03.925 --> 00:50:11.540 align:middle line:90%


00:50:11.540 --> 00:50:12.170 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:50:12.170 --> 00:50:13.340 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: 5/9.

00:50:13.340 --> 00:50:15.155 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: 5/9, yeah.

00:50:15.155 --> 00:50:23.570 align:middle line:90%


00:50:23.570 --> 00:50:25.700 align:middle line:90%
So let's break this down a bit.

00:50:25.700 --> 00:50:30.580 align:middle line:84%
So we're looking at the
probability of the set,

00:50:30.580 --> 00:50:35.080 align:middle line:84%
2, comma, 1, red wins;
6, 1, 6, 5, red wins;

00:50:35.080 --> 00:50:37.950 align:middle line:90%
and 7, 1, 7, 5, red wins.

00:50:37.950 --> 00:50:41.950 align:middle line:90%


00:50:41.950 --> 00:50:56.440 align:middle line:90%
So 2, 1, 6, 1, 6, 5, 7, 1, 7, 5.

00:50:56.440 --> 00:50:58.780 align:middle line:90%
We have five of these.

00:50:58.780 --> 00:51:00.985 align:middle line:90%
So that's 5/9.

00:51:00.985 --> 00:51:17.991 align:middle line:90%


00:51:17.991 --> 00:51:21.550 align:middle line:84%
Now, what if instead
we had red versus blue

00:51:21.550 --> 00:51:22.785 align:middle line:90%
instead of red versus green?

00:51:22.785 --> 00:51:31.040 align:middle line:90%


00:51:31.040 --> 00:51:34.140 align:middle line:84%
So if instead of red versus
green, we have red versus blue,

00:51:34.140 --> 00:51:40.380 align:middle line:84%
this column now gets replaced
with 3, 4, 8 instead of 1, 5, 9.

00:51:40.380 --> 00:51:45.428 align:middle line:90%


00:51:45.428 --> 00:51:49.490 align:middle line:84%
So our tree diagram is going
to look like the following.

00:51:49.490 --> 00:51:53.690 align:middle line:90%
So we've still got 2, 6, 7 here.

00:51:53.690 --> 00:51:57.840 align:middle line:84%
But this time, this is
going to be 3, 4, 8--

00:51:57.840 --> 00:52:01.460 align:middle line:90%


00:52:01.460 --> 00:52:06.590 align:middle line:90%
3, 4, 8, 3, 4, 8.

00:52:06.590 --> 00:52:10.310 align:middle line:90%


00:52:10.310 --> 00:52:13.190 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to omit the
probabilities because, as we

00:52:13.190 --> 00:52:14.670 align:middle line:90%
just established, it's uniform.

00:52:14.670 --> 00:52:16.003 align:middle line:90%
So it's just a counting problem.

00:52:16.003 --> 00:52:24.446 align:middle line:90%


00:52:24.446 --> 00:52:25.863 align:middle line:84%
But let's write
down the outcomes.

00:52:25.863 --> 00:52:41.994 align:middle line:90%


00:52:41.994 --> 00:52:44.525 align:middle line:84%
So in how many of these
outcomes does red win?

00:52:44.525 --> 00:52:48.600 align:middle line:90%


00:52:48.600 --> 00:52:54.930 align:middle line:84%
Well, not this one, not
this one, not this one.

00:52:54.930 --> 00:53:01.990 align:middle line:84%
So if red rolls 2, all of blue's
numbers are going to be higher,

00:53:01.990 --> 00:53:04.290 align:middle line:90%
so blue is always going to win.

00:53:04.290 --> 00:53:09.810 align:middle line:84%
If red rolls 6, red wins
if blue rolls 3 or 4;

00:53:09.810 --> 00:53:13.925 align:middle line:84%
loses if blue rolls
8, and same for 7.

00:53:13.925 --> 00:53:19.662 align:middle line:90%


00:53:19.662 --> 00:53:26.820 align:middle line:84%
So we have four
outcomes where red wins.

00:53:26.820 --> 00:53:28.353 align:middle line:84%
So red wins with
probability 4/9.

00:53:28.353 --> 00:53:35.012 align:middle line:90%


00:53:35.012 --> 00:53:45.967 align:middle line:84%
So we just saw that red beats
green but loses to blue.

00:53:45.967 --> 00:53:47.800 align:middle line:84%
What does that tell us
about blue and green?

00:53:47.800 --> 00:53:50.630 align:middle line:90%


00:53:50.630 --> 00:53:52.720 align:middle line:84%
If I pick blue, and you
pick green, what happens?

00:53:52.720 --> 00:53:55.460 align:middle line:90%


00:53:55.460 --> 00:53:56.200 align:middle line:90%
Who wins?

00:53:56.200 --> 00:54:00.080 align:middle line:90%


00:54:00.080 --> 00:54:00.770 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:54:00.770 --> 00:54:01.850 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Green.

00:54:01.850 --> 00:54:02.820 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Green.

00:54:02.820 --> 00:54:04.180 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:54:04.180 --> 00:54:06.680 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:54:06.680 --> 00:54:08.575 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: OK,
so green beats red.

00:54:08.575 --> 00:54:11.660 align:middle line:90%


00:54:11.660 --> 00:54:15.025 align:middle line:84%
So I think we just established
that red beats green, right?

00:54:15.025 --> 00:54:20.720 align:middle line:90%


00:54:20.720 --> 00:54:26.580 align:middle line:84%
So here, we've got
red beats green.

00:54:26.580 --> 00:54:29.585 align:middle line:84%
Here, we've got
red loses to blue.

00:54:29.585 --> 00:54:33.570 align:middle line:90%


00:54:33.570 --> 00:54:38.460 align:middle line:84%
So if we have
green and blue, who

00:54:38.460 --> 00:54:41.910 align:middle line:90%
thinks that green should win?

00:54:41.910 --> 00:54:44.040 align:middle line:90%
Who thinks that blue should win?

00:54:44.040 --> 00:54:46.320 align:middle line:90%
Who has absolutely no idea?

00:54:46.320 --> 00:54:49.710 align:middle line:84%
Who wants to do
the tree diagram?

00:54:49.710 --> 00:54:51.448 align:middle line:84%
Oh, still pretty
enthusiastic about that,

00:54:51.448 --> 00:54:52.990 align:middle line:84%
even though we've
got some intuition.

00:54:52.990 --> 00:54:54.660 align:middle line:90%
That's great.

00:54:54.660 --> 00:54:56.170 align:middle line:90%
Intuition is bad.

00:54:56.170 --> 00:54:57.580 align:middle line:90%
Discard the intuition.

00:54:57.580 --> 00:55:00.570 align:middle line:90%


00:55:00.570 --> 00:55:05.910 align:middle line:84%
OK, so if we've got
green versus blue,

00:55:05.910 --> 00:55:08.590 align:middle line:84%
so this can be the
green roll here.

00:55:08.590 --> 00:55:12.150 align:middle line:90%
We've got 1, 5, 9.

00:55:12.150 --> 00:55:23.320 align:middle line:84%
Blue roll can be 3, 4,
8, 3, 4, 8, 3, 4, 8.

00:55:23.320 --> 00:55:26.920 align:middle line:90%


00:55:26.920 --> 00:55:29.650 align:middle line:84%
So in which of these
does green win?

00:55:29.650 --> 00:55:33.520 align:middle line:84%
Well, if green rolls 1,
then green is screwed.

00:55:33.520 --> 00:55:37.990 align:middle line:84%
So all of these
are bad for green.

00:55:37.990 --> 00:55:43.210 align:middle line:84%
If green rolls 5, well, 5
will beat 3 and 4, but not 8.

00:55:43.210 --> 00:55:47.740 align:middle line:90%
So green wins these two.

00:55:47.740 --> 00:55:51.855 align:middle line:84%
And if green rolls 9, then
green beats whatever blue rolls.

00:55:51.855 --> 00:55:56.870 align:middle line:90%


00:55:56.870 --> 00:55:59.025 align:middle line:84%
So it looks like green is
winning in five of these.

00:55:59.025 --> 00:56:14.435 align:middle line:90%


00:56:14.435 --> 00:56:18.090 align:middle line:90%
So this should be like that.

00:56:18.090 --> 00:56:25.050 align:middle line:90%


00:56:25.050 --> 00:56:31.050 align:middle line:84%
So red beats green, green
beats blue, and blue beats red.

00:56:31.050 --> 00:56:32.000 align:middle line:90%
What's gone wrong?

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:40.800 align:middle line:90%


00:56:40.800 --> 00:56:41.696 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:56:41.696 --> 00:56:44.480 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:56:44.480 --> 00:56:45.480 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Pardon?

00:56:45.480 --> 00:56:48.570 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: There is only
a hierarchy [INAUDIBLE].

00:56:48.570 --> 00:56:49.650 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah.

00:56:49.650 --> 00:56:51.520 align:middle line:90%
So nothing's gone wrong.

00:56:51.520 --> 00:56:54.420 align:middle line:84%
All that's gone wrong
is I kind of expected

00:56:54.420 --> 00:56:57.570 align:middle line:84%
that there would be a
linear order on them.

00:56:57.570 --> 00:56:59.920 align:middle line:84%
If red beats green
and green beats blue,

00:56:59.920 --> 00:57:01.440 align:middle line:84%
it kind of intuitively
makes sense

00:57:01.440 --> 00:57:02.980 align:middle line:84%
that red should
beat blue, right?

00:57:02.980 --> 00:57:05.550 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:57:05.550 --> 00:57:07.210 align:middle line:90%
No, no intuition.

00:57:07.210 --> 00:57:09.510 align:middle line:90%
Just do the tree diagram.

00:57:09.510 --> 00:57:12.520 align:middle line:84%
So yeah, this is
perfectly fine, right?

00:57:12.520 --> 00:57:14.150 align:middle line:84%
And, in fact, it
gets even weirder.

00:57:14.150 --> 00:57:17.488 align:middle line:90%


00:57:17.488 --> 00:57:21.110 align:middle line:84%
What do you think happens
if we each choose two dice--

00:57:21.110 --> 00:57:22.360 align:middle line:90%
or, sorry, we each roll twice?

00:57:22.360 --> 00:57:27.250 align:middle line:90%


00:57:27.250 --> 00:57:33.200 align:middle line:84%
So what if I pick the
red die; I roll it twice;

00:57:33.200 --> 00:57:37.090 align:middle line:84%
you pick the green
die; you roll it twice?

00:57:37.090 --> 00:57:39.250 align:middle line:84%
Red probably beats
green, so is it true

00:57:39.250 --> 00:57:41.770 align:middle line:84%
that two red rolls probably
beat two green rolls

00:57:41.770 --> 00:57:42.600 align:middle line:90%
if we sum them up?

00:57:42.600 --> 00:57:48.280 align:middle line:90%


00:57:48.280 --> 00:57:51.130 align:middle line:90%
Who thinks yes?

00:57:51.130 --> 00:57:53.290 align:middle line:90%
Who thinks no?

00:57:53.290 --> 00:57:55.600 align:middle line:84%
Who wants to draw
the tree diagram?

00:57:55.600 --> 00:57:57.560 align:middle line:90%
Oh, wow, so eager.

00:57:57.560 --> 00:57:58.550 align:middle line:90%
I don't.

00:57:58.550 --> 00:58:02.941 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

00:58:02.941 --> 00:58:06.730 align:middle line:84%
What is the tree diagram going
to look like if we do that?

00:58:06.730 --> 00:58:08.420 align:middle line:90%
I'm rolling twice.

00:58:08.420 --> 00:58:09.890 align:middle line:90%
You're rolling twice.

00:58:09.890 --> 00:58:15.240 align:middle line:84%
Each roll can have
three possibilities.

00:58:15.240 --> 00:58:20.240 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to end up
with a pretty massive tree.

00:58:20.240 --> 00:58:23.750 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to draw that,
at least not on the board.

00:58:23.750 --> 00:58:26.600 align:middle line:84%
Does somebody else want
to come up and do it?

00:58:26.600 --> 00:58:28.010 align:middle line:90%
Please?

00:58:28.010 --> 00:58:29.450 align:middle line:90%
No, nobody?

00:58:29.450 --> 00:58:33.750 align:middle line:84%
OK, well, instead of drawing
out the entire tree diagram,

00:58:33.750 --> 00:58:36.775 align:middle line:84%
let's start drawing it and
see if we can find a pattern.

00:58:36.775 --> 00:58:41.795 align:middle line:90%


00:58:41.795 --> 00:58:47.233 align:middle line:90%
So this is R2 versus G2.

00:58:47.233 --> 00:58:51.746 align:middle line:90%


00:58:51.746 --> 00:58:58.950 align:middle line:84%
So let's start by
drawing as we did before.

00:58:58.950 --> 00:59:02.780 align:middle line:90%
So my first roll, that was red.

00:59:02.780 --> 00:59:05.960 align:middle line:90%
It could be 2, 6, or 7.

00:59:05.960 --> 00:59:08.790 align:middle line:84%
Second roll could
also be 2, 6, or 7.

00:59:08.790 --> 00:59:21.406 align:middle line:90%


00:59:21.406 --> 00:59:28.510 align:middle line:84%
Now, for green, we're
basically just going

00:59:28.510 --> 00:59:32.980 align:middle line:84%
to be drawing the same tree
nine times, so let's not.

00:59:32.980 --> 00:59:40.900 align:middle line:84%
So green could roll 1, 5,
9, and then can also roll

00:59:40.900 --> 00:59:43.965 align:middle line:90%
1, 5, 9 for the second roll.

00:59:43.965 --> 00:59:52.132 align:middle line:90%


00:59:52.132 --> 00:59:55.120 align:middle line:84%
And rather than duplicating
this tree nine times,

00:59:55.120 --> 00:59:57.860 align:middle line:84%
I'm just going to
leave this as it is.

00:59:57.860 --> 00:59:59.850 align:middle line:84%
And we can see if we
can find a pattern.

00:59:59.850 --> 01:00:04.012 align:middle line:90%


01:00:04.012 --> 01:00:05.990 align:middle line:84%
Does that make
sense to everybody?

01:00:05.990 --> 01:00:12.710 align:middle line:90%


01:00:12.710 --> 01:00:19.490 align:middle line:84%
So an outcome now is going to
be a 4-tuple, instead of a pair.

01:00:19.490 --> 01:00:23.240 align:middle line:84%
And in some sense,
we can think of it

01:00:23.240 --> 01:00:29.960 align:middle line:84%
as combining a leaf of this
tree with a leaf of this tree.

01:00:29.960 --> 01:00:32.300 align:middle line:84%
We're going to take a red
leaf and a green leaf.

01:00:32.300 --> 01:00:32.810 align:middle line:90%
Question?

01:00:32.810 --> 01:00:34.790 align:middle line:90%
Or no?

01:00:34.790 --> 01:00:35.960 align:middle line:90%
No, OK.

01:00:35.960 --> 01:00:42.230 align:middle line:90%


01:00:42.230 --> 01:00:49.391 align:middle line:84%
So we can then abbreviate
it even further.

01:00:49.391 --> 01:00:52.920 align:middle line:84%
Instead of looking at the pair
of numbers that we've rolled,

01:00:52.920 --> 01:00:57.020 align:middle line:84%
let's instead look
at just the sum.

01:00:57.020 --> 01:01:02.420 align:middle line:84%
So if red rolls two
2's, we've got 4 here.

01:01:02.420 --> 01:01:04.220 align:middle line:90%
2 and 6 is 8.

01:01:04.220 --> 01:01:06.830 align:middle line:90%
2 and 7 is 9.

01:01:06.830 --> 01:01:09.855 align:middle line:90%
6, 2 is 8.

01:01:09.855 --> 01:01:10.990 align:middle line:90%
6, 6 is not 9.

01:01:10.990 --> 01:01:12.480 align:middle line:90%
That's 12.

01:01:12.480 --> 01:01:14.550 align:middle line:90%
Never trust me to do arithmetic.

01:01:14.550 --> 01:01:16.170 align:middle line:90%
6, 7 is 13.

01:01:16.170 --> 01:01:17.880 align:middle line:90%
7 and 2 is 9.

01:01:17.880 --> 01:01:19.470 align:middle line:90%
7 and 6 is 13.

01:01:19.470 --> 01:01:20.630 align:middle line:90%
7 and 7 is 14.

01:01:20.630 --> 01:01:25.278 align:middle line:90%


01:01:25.278 --> 01:01:27.850 align:middle line:84%
And if we do the
same thing for green,

01:01:27.850 --> 01:01:38.005 align:middle line:84%
we have 2, 6, 10, 6,
10, 14, 10, 14, 18.

01:01:38.005 --> 01:01:45.438 align:middle line:90%


01:01:45.438 --> 01:01:50.130 align:middle line:84%
So now we can start
counting outcomes.

01:01:50.130 --> 01:01:52.780 align:middle line:84%
If we take this leaf
of the red tree,

01:01:52.780 --> 01:01:56.040 align:middle line:84%
how many outcomes are
there where red wins?

01:01:56.040 --> 01:01:59.520 align:middle line:84%
If red rolls four in
total, the only way

01:01:59.520 --> 01:02:03.970 align:middle line:84%
that red wins is if
green gets snake eyes.

01:02:03.970 --> 01:02:05.015 align:middle line:90%
So we've just got one.

01:02:05.015 --> 01:02:09.770 align:middle line:90%


01:02:09.770 --> 01:02:14.270 align:middle line:84%
If red rolls 8, which could
be either of these two,

01:02:14.270 --> 01:02:17.990 align:middle line:84%
how many outcomes are
there where red wins?

01:02:17.990 --> 01:02:21.890 align:middle line:84%
Well, we've got the 2 here,
a 6 here, and a 6 here.

01:02:21.890 --> 01:02:22.780 align:middle line:90%
So we've got three.

01:02:22.780 --> 01:02:25.880 align:middle line:90%


01:02:25.880 --> 01:02:30.500 align:middle line:84%
And we've got two red
leaves that have 8.

01:02:30.500 --> 01:02:31.320 align:middle line:90%
What about 9?

01:02:31.320 --> 01:02:34.520 align:middle line:84%
It looks like we've got
two more that have 9.

01:02:34.520 --> 01:02:38.140 align:middle line:84%
Same deal-- we don't have any
8's or 9's over on this side.

01:02:38.140 --> 01:02:43.940 align:middle line:90%


01:02:43.940 --> 01:02:45.330 align:middle line:90%
What else do we have?

01:02:45.330 --> 01:02:47.540 align:middle line:90%
12.

01:02:47.540 --> 01:02:51.830 align:middle line:84%
OK, well, if red
rolls 12, then red

01:02:51.830 --> 01:02:55.620 align:middle line:84%
is good if blue rolls 2,
6, 10, but not 14 or 18.

01:02:55.620 --> 01:02:59.143 align:middle line:84%
So we've got 1, 2,
3, 4, 5, 6 outcomes.

01:02:59.143 --> 01:03:01.880 align:middle line:90%


01:03:01.880 --> 01:03:05.800 align:middle line:84%
And we have one red
leaf where red has 12.

01:03:05.800 --> 01:03:08.481 align:middle line:90%


01:03:08.481 --> 01:03:09.880 align:middle line:90%
And then same thing for 13--

01:03:09.880 --> 01:03:14.220 align:middle line:84%
there are no 12's or 13's over
here, and we have two 13's.

01:03:14.220 --> 01:03:19.560 align:middle line:90%


01:03:19.560 --> 01:03:23.100 align:middle line:90%
Now, what about 14?

01:03:23.100 --> 01:03:28.170 align:middle line:84%
Well, if red rolls
14, then same deal.

01:03:28.170 --> 01:03:29.915 align:middle line:84%
But we've got these
two ties here.

01:03:29.915 --> 01:03:35.490 align:middle line:90%


01:03:35.490 --> 01:03:36.943 align:middle line:90%
So red wins.

01:03:36.943 --> 01:03:40.500 align:middle line:90%


01:03:40.500 --> 01:03:43.050 align:middle line:90%
Draw, we've just got two.

01:03:43.050 --> 01:03:45.790 align:middle line:84%
And then red loses is
going to be the complement.

01:03:45.790 --> 01:03:59.800 align:middle line:90%


01:03:59.800 --> 01:04:02.640 align:middle line:84%
So has anybody added
all of these up yet?

01:04:02.640 --> 01:04:03.485 align:middle line:90%
I haven't.

01:04:03.485 --> 01:04:07.012 align:middle line:90%


01:04:07.012 --> 01:04:11.965 align:middle line:90%
5, 30, 42, 43, is that right?

01:04:11.965 --> 01:04:15.277 align:middle line:90%


01:04:15.277 --> 01:04:15.860 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:04:15.860 --> 01:04:22.850 align:middle line:90%


01:04:22.850 --> 01:04:26.845 align:middle line:84%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: OK, so
43 outcomes for red wins.

01:04:26.845 --> 01:04:39.500 align:middle line:90%


01:04:39.500 --> 01:04:40.768 align:middle line:90%
Is something wrong?

01:04:40.768 --> 01:04:41.935 align:middle line:90%
This doesn't match my notes.

01:04:41.935 --> 01:04:46.130 align:middle line:90%


01:04:46.130 --> 01:04:47.840 align:middle line:90%
Let's see.

01:04:47.840 --> 01:04:52.070 align:middle line:90%
So we've got 1 for this subtree.

01:04:52.070 --> 01:04:55.700 align:middle line:90%
For each of these, we have 3.

01:04:55.700 --> 01:04:59.200 align:middle line:84%
For each of the
9's, we also have 3,

01:04:59.200 --> 01:05:03.453 align:middle line:90%
so that's those, 12, 13, and 13.

01:05:03.453 --> 01:05:07.200 align:middle line:90%


01:05:07.200 --> 01:05:08.900 align:middle line:84%
Oh, do I just have
too many terms?

01:05:08.900 --> 01:05:10.025 align:middle line:90%
I just have too many terms.

01:05:10.025 --> 01:05:13.200 align:middle line:90%


01:05:13.200 --> 01:05:14.256 align:middle line:90%
OK, not 43.

01:05:14.256 --> 01:05:14.923 align:middle line:90%
It should be 37.

01:05:14.923 --> 01:05:17.730 align:middle line:90%


01:05:17.730 --> 01:05:19.740 align:middle line:90%
Is that right?

01:05:19.740 --> 01:05:25.470 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, or 12, 13, 13,
and 14 each have 6.

01:05:25.470 --> 01:05:26.460 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:05:26.460 --> 01:05:28.020 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: OK.

01:05:28.020 --> 01:05:31.090 align:middle line:84%
OK, yeah, never trust
me to do arithmetic.

01:05:31.090 --> 01:05:32.790 align:middle line:90%
It's always a bad plan.

01:05:32.790 --> 01:05:36.850 align:middle line:84%
OK, so red wins in
37 of the outcomes.

01:05:36.850 --> 01:05:38.620 align:middle line:90%
There's a draw in 2 of them.

01:05:38.620 --> 01:05:40.430 align:middle line:84%
And how many outcomes
are there in total?

01:05:40.430 --> 01:05:46.770 align:middle line:90%


01:05:46.770 --> 01:05:47.880 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:05:47.880 --> 01:05:48.910 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Is that 81?

01:05:48.910 --> 01:05:50.230 align:middle line:90%
BRYNMOR CHAPMAN: Yeah, 81.

01:05:50.230 --> 01:05:59.130 align:middle line:84%
So red loses in 81 minus 37
minus 2, which is that 42?

01:05:59.130 --> 01:06:00.020 align:middle line:90%
I think that's 42.

01:06:00.020 --> 01:06:03.742 align:middle line:90%


01:06:03.742 --> 01:06:12.830 align:middle line:84%
So because this is a uniform
space, we have 37/81, 42/81,

01:06:12.830 --> 01:06:15.770 align:middle line:84%
which is going to be-- well,
actually, let's not reduce it.

01:06:15.770 --> 01:06:18.190 align:middle line:90%
It's easier to see like that.

01:06:18.190 --> 01:06:19.845 align:middle line:90%
And 2 out of 81 for a draw.

01:06:19.845 --> 01:06:22.630 align:middle line:90%


01:06:22.630 --> 01:06:27.500 align:middle line:84%
So if we only had one roll,
red had the advantage.

01:06:27.500 --> 01:06:29.680 align:middle line:84%
Red wins with
probability of 5/9.

01:06:29.680 --> 01:06:33.850 align:middle line:84%
If we have two rolls, the
probability that red wins

01:06:33.850 --> 01:06:36.728 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than the
probability that red loses.

01:06:36.728 --> 01:06:38.770 align:middle line:84%
So now suddenly, green
has the advantage instead.

01:06:38.770 --> 01:06:41.800 align:middle line:90%


01:06:41.800 --> 01:06:47.080 align:middle line:84%
And as it turns
out, the same thing

01:06:47.080 --> 01:06:50.650 align:middle line:84%
happens with all
three pairs of dice.

01:06:50.650 --> 01:06:55.430 align:middle line:84%
So red beats green
with one roll.

01:06:55.430 --> 01:06:57.530 align:middle line:90%
Green beats blue with one roll.

01:06:57.530 --> 01:07:01.140 align:middle line:84%
But blue beats green
with two rolls.

01:07:01.140 --> 01:07:04.320 align:middle line:84%
And blue beats red
with one roll, but red

01:07:04.320 --> 01:07:07.410 align:middle line:90%
beats blue with two rolls.

01:07:07.410 --> 01:07:13.320 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, so the dice
continue to not have

01:07:13.320 --> 01:07:15.130 align:middle line:90%
this transitivity property.

01:07:15.130 --> 01:07:19.554 align:middle line:90%
But every time, it switched.

01:07:19.554 --> 01:07:26.290 align:middle line:84%
And as it turns out, you
can even extend this.

01:07:26.290 --> 01:07:29.440 align:middle line:84%
Like if you have more dice
with different numbers,

01:07:29.440 --> 01:07:35.070 align:middle line:84%
you can get all sorts of weird
things that could happen.

01:07:35.070 --> 01:07:38.880 align:middle line:84%
So there's a link to a
rather interesting paper

01:07:38.880 --> 01:07:43.980 align:middle line:84%
on arXiv if you want to see
it in the lecture notes.

01:07:43.980 --> 01:07:47.200 align:middle line:84%
But yeah, for now, I think
that's all we have time for.

01:07:47.200 --> 01:07:49.660 align:middle line:84%
Feel free to come up
if you have questions.

01:07:49.660 --> 01:07:52.850 align:middle line:84%
And otherwise, we will
see you on Thursday.

01:07:52.850 --> 01:07:59.000 align:middle line:90%